{"title_page": "Gentleman Ghost", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character}}\n{{Infobox comics character <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image= JSA-86-int.jpg\n|imagesize= <!-- numeral only, defaults to 250 -->\n|converted = y\n|caption = Gentleman Ghost facing [[Alan Scott]] from ''JSA'' #86,<br>by artist [[Luke Ross]]\n|character_name = Gentleman Ghost\n|real_name = James Craddock\n|publisher=[[DC Comics]]\n|debut = ''[[Flash Comics]]'' #88<br> (October 1947)\n|creators = [[Robert Kanigher]] (writer)<br>[[Joe Kubert]] (artist)\n|Base of operations = \n|species   = [[Ghost]]\n|homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n|alliances = [[Injustice Society]]<br>[[Secret Society of Super Villains]]<br>[[Suicide Squad]]\n|partners  = <!-- optional -->\n|supports  = <!-- optional -->\n|aliases   = The Ghost, \"Gentleman Jim\", Jim Craddock\n|powers    = Spectral ability to turn invisible and incorporeal<br>Renders anybody who touches him deathly cold<br>Teleportation<br>Adequate marksman with antique [[flintlock]] pistols<br>Interdimensional travel<br>Spectral energy projection<br>Control over undead<br>Enhanced speed, regeneration, and strength<br>Invokes a white horse that serves as a means of transport<br>Can create spectral weapons\n|cat      = super\n|subcat   = DC Comics\n|hero     = \n|villain  = y\n|sortkey  = Gentleman Ghost\n}}\n'''Gentleman Ghost''' is a [[fictional character|fictional]] comic book [[supervillain]] appearing in books published by [[DC Comics]] publications. Created by writer [[Robert Kanigher]] and artist [[Joe Kubert]], the character first appeared in ''[[Flash Comics]]'' #88 (October 1947).<ref name=Guide>{{cite book |last1=Cowsill |first1=Alan |last2=Irvine |first2=Alex |last3=Korte |first3=Steve |last4=Manning |first4=Matt |last5=Wiacek |first5=Win |last6=Wilson |first6=Sven |title=The DC Comics Encyclopedia: The Definitive Guide to the Characters of the DC Universe |date=2016 |publisher=DK Publishing |isbn=978-1-4654-5357-0 |page=119}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n'''James Craddock''' is the son of an English gentleman who abandoned both Jim and his mother, forcing them into poverty. Craddock grew up to become a notorious [[highwayman]] and robber who terrorized [[England]] in the 19th century under the name \"Gentleman Jim,\" after a prophecy from a gypsy said he would be a highwayman. He encountered the [[ghost]]s of other highwaymen and [[Dick Turpin]] left him a horse. He journeyed to the [[United States]] and encounters the [[gunslinger]]s [[Nighthawk (DC Comics)|Nighthawk]] and [[Cinnamon (comics)|Cinnamon]]. The hot-headed Nighthawk lynched Craddock after wrongly assuming that he sexually assaulted Cinnamon, but Craddock somehow eludes death to rise again as a ghost.\n\nThe Gentleman Ghost learns he must wander the earth until the [[spirit]] of his killer moves on to the next [[plane (metaphysics)|plane of existence]]. Unfortunately, Nighthawk and Cinnamon turn out to be the [[reincarnation]]s of [[Ancient Egypt]]ian royalty Prince Khufu and Chay-Ara: their [[soul]]s (due to their exposure to the [[Thanagar]]ian [[Nth metal]]) can never truly pass on. Both are eventually resurrected as [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]] and [[Hawkgirl]], and the Gentleman Ghost becomes their recurring nemesis during the 1940s.<ref name=\"dc-ency\">{{Citation | last = Wallace | first = Dan | author-link = | contribution = Gentleman Ghost | editor-last = Dougall | editor-first = Alastair | title = The DC Comics Encyclopedia | pages = 137 | publisher = [[Dorling Kindersley]] | place = New York | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-7566-4119-1 | oclc = 213309017}}</ref> Craddock has over the decades menaced other heroes, including [[Batman]], [[Atom (comics)|The Atom]], [[Flash (Barry Allen)|The Flash]], [[The New Teen Titans]], [[Max Mercury]] and [[Courtney Whitmore (comics)|Stargirl]], but the [[vengeful ghost]] always returns to his main foes, the Hawks, sometimes as a foe and sometimes as a friend.\n\nGentleman Ghost has clashed with [[Batman]] and [[Superman]] on different occasions. In ''JSA Classified'', issues 5-7, the Gentleman Ghost is a member of the [[Injustice Society]]. In ''[[Villains United]]'' #1, he joins the [[Secret Society of Super Villains]].\n\nHis origin is explored and altered in the pages of ''JSA'' #82-87 (2006). The [[Legitimacy (family law)|natural]] son of an abusive father and a poor mother, young Jim Craddock soon slips into a life of crime, making contacts with the supernatural. After a [[Romani people|gypsy]] prophesizes that he will be able to transcend death and return to life fighting and killing his enemies on English soil, his villainous career is put to an end when he is captured and sentenced to death by hanging after he is tricked by a woman he is trying to seduce who summons Redcoats. Returning as a ghost, he battles the JSA, hoping for the prophecy to come true.\n\nThe Ghost is briefly seen in the \"[[Infinite Crisis]]\" storyline, during the [[Secret Society of Supervillains]]' attack on Metropolis and its dozens of superpowered and human defenders. Afterwards, the Ghost becomes involved in a fight with [[Alan Scott]], which leaves Scott in a coma.\n\nWhen the rightful time arrives, the Ghost gains the additional power of summoning vengeful ghosts from his enemies' (the JSA) past, like someone Scott killed with an electrical accident, although this is a fake, and other highwaymen. His plan is foiled by [[Courtney Whitmore (comics)|Stargirl]], who, as a [[virginity|virgin]] girl, is impervious to ghostly attacks, an army of ghostly nobles who attack his army, and [[Wildcat (DC Comics)|Wildcat]], surprisingly a descendant of the Royal House of England, who decapitates him. Vanquished, he disappears.\n\nGentleman Ghost is seen as one of the villains sent to retrieve the Get Out of Hell Free card from the [[Secret Six (comics)|Secret Six]].\n\n===The New 52===\nIn [[The New 52]] (a 2011 reboot of the DC Comics universe), Gentleman Ghost is still a thief but no longer a ghost.<ref name=\"Gotham By Midnight Annual #1\">''Gotham By Midnight Annual'' #1</ref> In his first appearance, he steals the Mortis Orb, which has the power to resurrect the dead.<ref>''Savage Hawkman'' #5</ref> Hawkman deduces that Gentleman Ghost is Jim Craddock and Gentleman Ghost confirms it. Gentleman Ghost tells Hawkman he invited him here because the Nth metal drew him to the Mortis Orb. Then, he tells Hawkman he will take him to the orb, but Hawkman refuses, so Gentleman Ghost sends more apparitions after him, Hawkman escapes the building. Then, Gentleman Ghost appears again, saying that the warlock's spell rendered the orb inert years ago, but the Nth Metal broke the spell causing the orb to regain its power. Gentleman Ghost takes the orb, saying that he will use it to transcend death and resurrect himself through the life-force of every man, woman, and child nearby. Then, he disappears and the [[Zombie]]s attacking Hawkman fall apart.<ref>''Savage Hawkman'' #6</ref> Gentleman Ghost begins fully harnessing the orb\u2019s power, creating a portal from which Julius Gates comes out. Gates (demanding the orb) grabs Craddock, while Hawkman takes the orb from him. The portal vanishes with Craddock and Gates inside causing them both to disappear along with the apparitions and zombies. Hawkman drops the Mortis Orb somewhere in Antarctica to keep it from falling into the wrong hands again.<ref>''Savage Hawkman'' #7</ref>\n\nSometime later, Craddock took up residence in a New Hampshire called Duskhaven which he operated out of while he robbed wealthy socialites of Gotham. When the Midnight Shift apprehended him, he revealed his new origins. Some time in the past, Craddock had been a philanderer and drew the ire of a witch, who cursed him, granting his abilities but forcing him to commit criminal acts. He believed the curse would be lifted once the witch died, but it was not, and he found himself to be immortal.<ref name=\"Gotham By Midnight Annual #1\"/>\n\n==Powers and abilities==\n[[Image:Injustice society.jpg|thumb|150px|Gentleman Ghost in the [[Injustice Society]]. Art by [[Joe Bennett (penciller)|Joe Bennett]].]]\nOriginally, the Gentleman Ghost seemed to rely on devices to simulate a ghostly existence; the original 1940s stories left the question of his nature open to speculation. Later, however, he is [[retroactive continuity|retcon]]ned into a true ghost and his abilities altered to follow suit. As a ghost, Craddock has several abilities. He can become intangible and pass effortlessly through solid material. He can become completely invisible. In fact, the appearance of his head as a floating hat and monocle is actually him rendering his decayed face invisible. He has been shown as being able to teleport as short a distance as a few rooms or as far as across states. Gentleman Ghost can also summon spectral weapons including a cane that shoots spectral fire, and flintlock pistols. When passing through Craddock's ghostly form, people will sometimes experience an intense feeling of cold. Since this does not happen every time, it would seem that he can control this effect. Craddock can apparently track psionic energy and travel across dimensions as he did when he followed an astral tether from the Wizard to Johnny Sorrow. On certain occasions most of the manifestations of his abilities like teleportation and phasing are accompanied by a purple glow of spectral energy or transparent mist (possibly courtesy of different pencilers). Around the time of his prophesied return to life, he gains the power to summon and control the spirits of the dead due to his mother's spirit spending centuries recruiting them to help her son. It is unknown if he can still call upon them.\n\nThe Gentleman Ghost is apparently unable to touch or be touched by virgins. This is confirmed by his inability to do harm to both [[Courtney Whitmore (comics)|Stargirl]] and [[Jakeem Thunder]]. However, he can pick up a real weapon and be able to hurt them, as when he brandished the Cosmic Rod.\n\nAs a supernatural being, Gentleman Ghost cannot be killed and is very hard to hurt. However, those with royal blood can physically harm him and, when unaware, energy hitting him causes pain.\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in ''[[The All-New Super Friends Hour]]'', voiced by an uncredited [[Alan Oppenheimer]]. This version is referred to only as \"Gentleman Jim Craddock\" instead of \"Gentleman Ghost\". In the episode \"Ghost\", a man casts a spell to bring Gentleman Ghost to the living so that he can take revenge on [[Superman]] and [[Wonder Woman]] for imprisoning his spirit. He uses his powers to turn U.N. representatives into ghosts and later turns Superman and Wonder Woman into ghosts. The curse is eventually broken, after which the Super Friends used the mystical Rods of [[Merlin (DC Comics)|Merlin]] to send Gentleman Ghost back to his grave, never to return.\n* Gentleman Ghost was briefly considered to be featured in ''[[The New Batman Adventures]]''. When asked about his potential use in the show, producer and writer [[Paul Dini]] stated Gentleman Ghost's appearance would be \"likely, if we do more contemporary Batman stories.\" Ultimately, Gentleman Ghost never appeared in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsfinestonline.com/WF/sections/backstage/unused/batman/gentleman.php|title=The World's Finest - Backstage - Unused Villains Database - Gentleman Ghost|website=www.worldsfinestonline.com|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref>\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]'', voiced by [[Robin Atkin Downes]]. In \"I Am Legion\", he is seen as a member of [[Gorilla Grodd]]'s [[Secret Society of Super Villains|Secret Society]]. In the episode \"Ancient History\", he is shown trying to outrun the [[John Stewart (comics)|Green Lantern]] until [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]] catches him with a net made from Nth metal.\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in several episodes of the animated series ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'', voiced by [[Greg Ellis (actor)|Greg Ellis]]. In this version, \"Gentleman\" Jim Craddock was an infamous [[highwayman]] in 19th-century London who tried to obtain immortality by offering 10 souls to the demon [[Asteroth]] in exchange. However, he was stopped by the combined efforts of [[Sherlock Holmes]], the demon [[Etrigan]] and a time-displaced [[Batman]]. After being hung for his crimes, Craddock rose as Gentleman Ghost, swearing revenge on Batman (the demon stated that only \"his soul\" would not leave the earthly plane). Centuries later, he sought revenge by trying to kill Batman in several ways. However, Batman could defend himself with Nth metal.\n\n===Film===\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/dc/2016/12/12/new-lego-batman-movie-tv-spot-features-gentlemen-ghost-calendar-/|title=LEGO Batman Movie TV Spot with Gentleman Ghost, Calendar Man, and Condiment King|website=DC|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> He is among the villains that assist the [[Joker (character)|Joker]] in his attacks on Gotham City.\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in the direct-to-video film ''[[Teen Titans Go! vs. Teen Titans]]'', voiced by [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]].\n\n===Video games===\n* Gentleman Ghost also appears as a villain in ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold \u2013 The Videogame]]'', voiced again by [[Greg Ellis (actor)|Greg Ellis]]. Gentleman Ghost hires the [[Clock King]] to lure Batman to London, England, and later lures him and Hawkman into the underworld, in order to offer them to Astaroth as a sacrifice in exchange for his life back. When that fails, a vengeful Craddock attempts to bury them under, and later fights them in a graveyard. After being humiliated, Hawkman teaches Batman to have respect even for his enemies, and picks up the villain respectfully to take him to jail.\n* Gentleman Ghost also appears in ''[[DC Universe Online]]'', voiced by Jason Brenizer.\n* Gentleman Ghost appears as a playable character in ''[[Lego DC Super-Villains]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Batman Family adversaries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Timeline\n|before= \u2190 The first Harlequin was debuted by Robert Kanigher and Irwin Hasen. See [[Harlequin (comics)]] for more info and the previous timeline.\n|title= [[Timeline of DC Comics]] ([[Timeline of DC Comics (1940s)|1940s]]) \n|years= October 1947 \n|after = The first Icicle was debuted by Robert Kanigher and Irwin Hasen. See [[Icicle (comics)]] for more info and next timeline. \u2192\n}}\n{{Hawkman}}\n{{Justice League}}\n{{Justice Society of America}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional characters from parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Fictional murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional British people]]\n[[Category:Fictional English people]]\n[[Category:Fictional gentleman thieves]]\n[[Category:DC Comics supervillains]]\n[[Category:Fictional ghosts]]\n[[Category:DC Comics characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Golden Age supervillains]]\n[[Category:Earth-Two]]\n[[Category:Fictional undead]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1947]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Robert Kanigher]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Joe Kubert]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character}}\n{{Infobox comics character <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image= JSA-86-int.jpg\n|imagesize= <!-- numeral only, defaults to 250 -->\n|converted = y\n|caption = Gentleman Ghost facing [[Alan Scott]] from ''JSA'' #86,<br>by artist [[Luke Ross]]\n|character_name = Gentleman Ghost\n|real_name = James Craddock\n|publisher=[[DC Comics]]\n|debut = ''[[Flash Comics]]'' #88<br> (October 1947)\n|creators = [[Robert Kanigher]] (writer)<br>[[Joe Kubert]] (artist)\n|Base of operations = \n|species   = [[Ghost]]\n|homeworld = <!-- optional -->\n|alliances = [[Injustice Society]]<br>[[Secret Society of Super Villains]]<br>[[Suicide Squad]]\n|partners  = <!-- optional -->\n|supports  = <!-- optional -->\n|aliases   = The Ghost, \"Gentleman Jim\", Jim Craddock\n|powers    = Spectral ability to turn invisible and incorporeal<br>Renders anybody who touches him deathly cold<br>Teleportation<br>Adequate marksman with antique [[flintlock]] pistols<br>Interdimensional travel<br>Spectral energy projection<br>Control over undead<br>Enhanced speed, regeneration, and strength<br>Invokes a white horse that serves as a means of transport<br>Can create spectral weapons\n|cat      = super\n|subcat   = DC Comics\n|hero     = \n|villain  = y\n|sortkey  = Gentleman Ghost\n}}\n'''Gentleman Ghost''' is a [[fictional character|fictional]] comic book [[supervillain]] appearing in books published by [[DC Comics]] publications. Created by writer [[Robert Kanigher]] and artist [[Joe Kubert]], the character first appeared in ''[[Flash Comics]]'' #88 (October 1947).<ref name=Guide>{{cite book |last1=Cowsill |first1=Alan |last2=Irvine |first2=Alex |last3=Korte |first3=Steve |last4=Manning |first4=Matt |last5=Wiacek |first5=Win |last6=Wilson |first6=Sven |title=The DC Comics Encyclopedia: The Definitive Guide to the Characters of the DC Universe |date=2016 |publisher=DK Publishing |isbn=978-1-4654-5357-0 |page=119}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\n'''James Craddock''' is the son of an English gentleman who abandoned both Jim and his mother, forcing them into poverty. Craddock grew up to become a notorious [[highwayman]] and robber who terrorized [[England]] in the 19th century under the name \"Gentleman Jim,\" after a prophecy from a gypsy said he would be a highwayman. He encountered the [[ghost]]s of other highwaymen and [[Dick Turpin]] left him a horse. He journeyed to the [[United States]] and encounters the [[gunslinger]]s [[Nighthawk (DC Comics)|Nighthawk]] and [[Cinnamon (comics)|Cinnamon]]. The hot-headed Nighthawk lynched Craddock after wrongly assuming that he sexually assaulted Cinnamon, but Craddock somehow eludes death to rise again as a ghost.\n\nThe Gentleman Ghost learns he must wander the earth until the [[spirit]] of his killer moves on to the next [[plane (metaphysics)|plane of existence]]. Unfortunately, Nighthawk and Cinnamon turn out to be the [[reincarnation]]s of [[Ancient Egypt]]ian royalty Prince Khufu and Chay-Ara: their [[soul]]s (due to their exposure to the [[Thanagar]]ian [[Nth metal]]) can never truly pass on. Both are eventually resurrected as [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]] and [[Hawkgirl]], and the Gentleman Ghost becomes their recurring nemesis during the 1940s.<ref name=\"dc-ency\">{{Citation | last = Wallace | first = Dan | author-link = | contribution = Gentleman Ghost | editor-last = Dougall | editor-first = Alastair | title = The DC Comics Encyclopedia | pages = 137 | publisher = [[Dorling Kindersley]] | place = New York | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-7566-4119-1 | oclc = 213309017}}</ref> Craddock has over the decades menaced other heroes, including [[Batman]], [[Atom (comics)|The Atom]], [[Flash (Barry Allen)|The Flash]], [[The New Teen Titans]], [[Max Mercury]] and [[Courtney Whitmore (comics)|Stargirl]], but the [[vengeful ghost]] always returns to his main foes, the Hawks, sometimes as a foe and sometimes as a friend.\n\nGentleman Ghost has clashed with [[Batman]] and [[Superman]] on different occasions. In ''JSA Classified'', issues 5-7, the Gentleman Ghost is a member of the [[Injustice Society]]. In ''[[Villains United]]'' #1, he joins the [[Secret Society of Super Villains]].\n\nHis origin is explored and altered in the pages of ''JSA'' #82-87 (2006). The [[Legitimacy (family law)|natural]] son of an abusive father and a poor mother, young Jim Craddock soon slips into a life of crime, making contacts with the supernatural. After a [[Romani people|gypsy]] prophesizes that he will be able to transcend death and return to life fighting and killing his enemies on English soil, his villainous career is put to an end when he is captured and sentenced to death by hanging after he is tricked by a woman he is trying to seduce who summons Redcoats. Returning as a ghost, he battles the JSA, hoping for the prophecy to come true.\n\nThe Ghost is briefly seen in the \"[[Infinite Crisis]]\" storyline, during the [[Secret Society of Supervillains]]' attack on Metropolis and its dozens of superpowered and human defenders. Afterwards, the Ghost becomes involved in a fight with [[Alan Scott]], which leaves Scott in a coma.\n\nWhen the rightful time arrives, the Ghost gains the additional power of summoning vengeful ghosts from his enemies' (the JSA) past, like someone Scott killed with an electrical accident, although this is a fake, and other highwaymen. His plan is foiled by [[Courtney Whitmore (comics)|Stargirl]], who, as a [[virginity|virgin]] girl, is impervious to ghostly attacks, an army of ghostly nobles who attack his army, and [[Wildcat (comics)|Wildcat]], surprisingly a descendant of the Royal House of England, who decapitates him. Vanquished, he disappears.\n\nGentleman Ghost is seen as one of the villains sent to retrieve the Get Out of Hell Free card from the [[Secret Six (comics)|Secret Six]].\n\n===The New 52===\nIn [[The New 52]] (a 2011 reboot of the DC Comics universe), Gentleman Ghost is still a thief but no longer a ghost.<ref name=\"Gotham By Midnight Annual #1\">''Gotham By Midnight Annual'' #1</ref> In his first appearance, he steals the Mortis Orb, which has the power to resurrect the dead.<ref>''Savage Hawkman'' #5</ref> Hawkman deduces that Gentleman Ghost is Jim Craddock and Gentleman Ghost confirms it. Gentleman Ghost tells Hawkman he invited him here because the Nth metal drew him to the Mortis Orb. Then, he tells Hawkman he will take him to the orb, but Hawkman refuses, so Gentleman Ghost sends more apparitions after him, Hawkman escapes the building. Then, Gentleman Ghost appears again, saying that the warlock's spell rendered the orb inert years ago, but the Nth Metal broke the spell causing the orb to regain its power. Gentleman Ghost takes the orb, saying that he will use it to transcend death and resurrect himself through the life-force of every man, woman, and child nearby. Then, he disappears and the [[Zombie]]s attacking Hawkman fall apart.<ref>''Savage Hawkman'' #6</ref> Gentleman Ghost begins fully harnessing the orb\u2019s power, creating a portal from which Julius Gates comes out. Gates (demanding the orb) grabs Craddock, while Hawkman takes the orb from him. The portal vanishes with Craddock and Gates inside causing them both to disappear along with the apparitions and zombies. Hawkman drops the Mortis Orb somewhere in Antarctica to keep it from falling into the wrong hands again.<ref>''Savage Hawkman'' #7</ref>\n\nSometime later, Craddock took up residence in a New Hampshire called Duskhaven which he operated out of while he robbed wealthy socialites of Gotham. When the Midnight Shift apprehended him, he revealed his new origins. Some time in the past, Craddock had been a philanderer and drew the ire of a witch, who cursed him, granting his abilities but forcing him to commit criminal acts. He believed the curse would be lifted once the witch died, but it was not, and he found himself to be immortal.<ref name=\"Gotham By Midnight Annual #1\"/>\n\n==Powers and abilities==\n[[Image:Injustice society.jpg|thumb|150px|Gentleman Ghost in the [[Injustice Society]]. Art by [[Joe Bennett (penciller)|Joe Bennett]].]]\nOriginally, the Gentleman Ghost seemed to rely on devices to simulate a ghostly existence; the original 1940s stories left the question of his nature open to speculation. Later, however, he is [[retroactive continuity|retcon]]ned into a true ghost and his abilities altered to follow suit. As a ghost, Craddock has several abilities. He can become intangible and pass effortlessly through solid material. He can become completely invisible. In fact, the appearance of his head as a floating hat and monocle is actually him rendering his decayed face invisible. He has been shown as being able to teleport as short a distance as a few rooms or as far as across states. Gentleman Ghost can also summon spectral weapons including a cane that shoots spectral fire, and flintlock pistols. When passing through Craddock's ghostly form, people will sometimes experience an intense feeling of cold. Since this does not happen every time, it would seem that he can control this effect. Craddock can apparently track psionic energy and travel across dimensions as he did when he followed an astral tether from the Wizard to Johnny Sorrow. On certain occasions most of the manifestations of his abilities like teleportation and phasing are accompanied by a purple glow of spectral energy or transparent mist (possibly courtesy of different pencilers). Around the time of his prophesied return to life, he gains the power to summon and control the spirits of the dead due to his mother's spirit spending centuries recruiting them to help her son. It is unknown if he can still call upon them.\n\nThe Gentleman Ghost is apparently unable to touch or be touched by virgins. This is confirmed by his inability to do harm to both [[Courtney Whitmore (comics)|Stargirl]] and [[Jakeem Thunder]]. However, he can pick up a real weapon and be able to hurt them, as when he brandished the Cosmic Rod.\n\nAs a supernatural being, Gentleman Ghost cannot be killed and is very hard to hurt. However, those with royal blood can physically harm him and, when unaware, energy hitting him causes pain.\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in ''[[The All-New Super Friends Hour]]'', voiced by an uncredited [[Alan Oppenheimer]]. This version is referred to only as \"Gentleman Jim Craddock\" instead of \"Gentleman Ghost\". In the episode \"Ghost\", a man casts a spell to bring Gentleman Ghost to the living so that he can take revenge on [[Superman]] and [[Wonder Woman]] for imprisoning his spirit. He uses his powers to turn U.N. representatives into ghosts and later turns Superman and Wonder Woman into ghosts. The curse is eventually broken, after which the Super Friends used the mystical Rods of [[Merlin (DC Comics)|Merlin]] to send Gentleman Ghost back to his grave, never to return.\n* Gentleman Ghost was briefly considered to be featured in ''[[The New Batman Adventures]]''. When asked about his potential use in the show, producer and writer [[Paul Dini]] stated Gentleman Ghost's appearance would be \"likely, if we do more contemporary Batman stories.\" Ultimately, Gentleman Ghost never appeared in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsfinestonline.com/WF/sections/backstage/unused/batman/gentleman.php|title=The World's Finest - Backstage - Unused Villains Database - Gentleman Ghost|website=www.worldsfinestonline.com|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref>\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]'', voiced by [[Robin Atkin Downes]]. In \"I Am Legion\", he is seen as a member of [[Gorilla Grodd]]'s [[Secret Society of Super Villains|Secret Society]]. In the episode \"Ancient History\", he is shown trying to outrun the [[John Stewart (comics)|Green Lantern]] until [[Hawkman (Carter Hall)|Hawkman]] catches him with a net made from Nth metal.\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in several episodes of the animated series ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold]]'', voiced by [[Greg Ellis (actor)|Greg Ellis]]. In this version, \"Gentleman\" Jim Craddock was an infamous [[highwayman]] in 19th-century London who tried to obtain immortality by offering 10 souls to the demon [[Asteroth]] in exchange. However, he was stopped by the combined efforts of [[Sherlock Holmes]], the demon [[Etrigan]] and a time-displaced [[Batman]]. After being hung for his crimes, Craddock rose as Gentleman Ghost, swearing revenge on Batman (the demon stated that only \"his soul\" would not leave the earthly plane). Centuries later, he sought revenge by trying to kill Batman in several ways. However, Batman could defend himself with Nth metal.\n\n===Film===\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/dc/2016/12/12/new-lego-batman-movie-tv-spot-features-gentlemen-ghost-calendar-/|title=LEGO Batman Movie TV Spot with Gentleman Ghost, Calendar Man, and Condiment King|website=DC|accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> He is among the villains that assist the [[Joker (character)|Joker]] in his attacks on Gotham City.\n* Gentleman Ghost appears in the direct-to-video film ''[[Teen Titans Go! vs. Teen Titans]]'', voiced by [[\"Weird Al\" Yankovic]].\n\n===Video games===\n* Gentleman Ghost also appears as a villain in ''[[Batman: The Brave and the Bold \u2013 The Videogame]]'', voiced again by [[Greg Ellis (actor)|Greg Ellis]]. Gentleman Ghost hires the [[Clock King]] to lure Batman to London, England, and later lures him and Hawkman into the underworld, in order to offer them to Astaroth as a sacrifice in exchange for his life back. When that fails, a vengeful Craddock attempts to bury them under, and later fights them in a graveyard. After being humiliated, Hawkman teaches Batman to have respect even for his enemies, and picks up the villain respectfully to take him to jail.\n* Gentleman Ghost also appears in ''[[DC Universe Online]]'', voiced by Jason Brenizer.\n* Gentleman Ghost appears as a playable character in ''[[Lego DC Super-Villains]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Batman Family adversaries]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Timeline\n|before= \u2190 The first Harlequin was debuted by Robert Kanigher and Irwin Hasen. See [[Harlequin (comics)]] for more info and the previous timeline.\n|title= [[Timeline of DC Comics]] ([[Timeline of DC Comics (1940s)|1940s]]) \n|years= October 1947 \n|after = The first Icicle was debuted by Robert Kanigher and Irwin Hasen. See [[Icicle (comics)]] for more info and next timeline. \u2192\n}}\n{{Hawkman}}\n{{Justice League}}\n{{Justice Society of America}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional characters from parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Fictional murderers]]\n[[Category:Fictional British people]]\n[[Category:Fictional English people]]\n[[Category:Fictional gentleman thieves]]\n[[Category:DC Comics supervillains]]\n[[Category:Fictional ghosts]]\n[[Category:DC Comics characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Golden Age supervillains]]\n[[Category:Earth-Two]]\n[[Category:Fictional undead]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1947]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Robert Kanigher]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Joe Kubert]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toWildcat (disambiguation)(link changed toWildcat (DC Comics)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gentleman_Ghost"}
{"title_page": "2000 Brazilian Grand Prix", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox Grand Prix race report\n|Type           = F1\n|Country        = Brazil\n|Grand Prix     = Brazilian\n|Date           = 26 March\n|Year           = 2000\n|Image          = Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace (AKA Interlagos) track map.svg\n|Caption        =\n|Details ref    = <ref name=CF1Brazil2000>{{cite web|title=2000 Brazilian GP: XXIX Grande Pr\u00eamio Marlboro do Brasil|url=http://www.chicanef1.com/racetit.pl?year=2000&gp=Brazilian%20GP|publisher=Chicane F1|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209211055/http://www.chicanef1.com/racetit.pl?year=2000&gp=Brazilian%20GP|archivedate=9 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=AF1Report>{{cite journal|last=Lupini|first=Michele|title=The Brazilian GP Review|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/lupini.html|work=Atlas F1|volume=6|number=13|date=29 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000822102241/http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/lupini.html|archivedate=22 August 2000|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GPCOMBrazil00>{{cite web|title=Grand Prix Results: Brazilian GP, 2000|url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr648.html|publisher=GrandPrix.com|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020102025837/http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr648.html|archivedate=2 January 2002|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|Race_No        = 2\n|Season_No      = 17\n|Official name  = XXIX Grande Pr\u00eamio Marlboro do Brasil\n|Location       = [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil\n|Course         = Permanent racing facility\n|Course_mi      = 2.677\n|Course_km      = 4.309\n|Distance_laps  = 71\n|Distance_mi    = 190.681\n|Distance_km    = 305.939 \n|Attendance     = 72,000\n|Weather        = Sunny, Air: {{convert|22|C|F}}, Track: {{convert|35|C|F}}\n|Pole_Driver    = [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]]\n|Pole_Team      = [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n|Pole_Time      = 1:14.111\n|Pole_Country   = Finland\n|Fast_Driver    = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|Fast_Team      = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Fast_Time      = 1:14.755\n|Fast_Lap       = 48\n|Fast_Country   = Germany\n|First_Driver   = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|First_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|First_Country  = Germany\n|Second_Driver  = [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n|Second_Team    = [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n|Second_Country = Italy\n|Third_Driver   = [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n|Third_Team     = [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n|Third_Country  = Germany\n|Lapchart       = {{F1Laps2000|BRA}}\n}}\nThe '''2000 Brazilian Grand Prix''' (officially the '''XXIX Grande Pr\u00eamio Marlboro do Brasil''') was a [[Formula One]] motor race held on 26 March 2000 at the [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]] in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil. 72,000 people attended the race, which was the second round of the [[2000 Formula One World Championship]] and the 29th overall edition of the [[Brazilian Grand Prix|event]]. [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] won the 71-lap race from a third-position start. [[Giancarlo Fisichella]] of the [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] team finished in second and [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]'s [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]] was third.\n\n[[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] of the [[McLaren]] team took [[pole position]] by recording the fastest lap in qualifying. He led on the first lap of the race before Michael Schumacher passed him at the start of lap two. Thereafter, Michael Schumacher opened up a 17.6 second lead before his first of two [[pit stop]]s for fuel and tyres on lap 20. He retook the lead after H\u00e4kkinen retired with a loss of engine oil pressure ten laps later. [[David Coulthard]] in the other McLaren gained on Michael Schumacher in the final 12 laps as the latter slowed to manage an [[oil pressure]] problem. He was not close enough to make a pass for the win and Michael Schumacher took his second consecutive victory of the season, his third in Brazil and the 37th of his career.\n\nAfter the race, Coulthard was disqualified from second place due to an illegal front wing endplate. McLaren filed an appeal to the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]'s International Court of Appeal, which was rejected. The disqualification advanced every driver behind Coulthard by a single position. The result extended Michael Schumacher's lead atop the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Drivers' Championship]] to 12 [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]]. Fisichella moved from fifth to second as [[Rubens Barrichello]] in the second Ferrari fell to third after not finishing the race. Ferrari further increased their lead in the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|Constructors' Championship]] to 18 points as Benetton advanced to second with fifteen races left in the season.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace, July 3, 2018 SkySat (cropped).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]] ''(pictured in 2018)'', where the race was held.]]\nThe 2000 [[Brazilian Grand Prix]] was the second of the 17 motor races in the [[2000 Formula One World Championship]] and the 29th overall edition of the event. It took place at the 15-turn {{convert|4.309|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]] in the Brazilian city of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] on 26 March.<ref name=CF1Brazil2000/><ref name=AF1Preview/> The high-altitude, anti-clockwise track had significant elevation changes, placing a heavy load of [[g-force]] on the left-hand side of drivers' necks. Teams altered their cars to run at medium to high levels of [[downforce]] and the [[Damper (flow)|dampers]], [[Coil spring|springs]] and [[Suspension (vehicle)|suspensions]] were optimised to adapt to the bumpy track surface.<ref name=\"AF1Preview\" /> Formula One's control [[Formula One tyre|tyre]] supplier [[Bridgestone]] brought the soft and the medium dry compound tyres to the race.<ref name=AF1Preview>{{cite journal|last=Tytler|first=Ewan|title=The Brazilian GP Preview|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/preview/tytler.html|journal=Atlas F1|volume=6|number=12|date=22 March 2000|accessdate=31 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000510041938/http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/preview/tytler.html|archivedate=10 May 2000}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning the preceding [[2000 Australian Grand Prix|Australian Grand Prix]]\u2014the first of the 17 World Championship races\u2014[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] led the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Drivers' Championship]] with ten [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]]; his teammate [[Rubens Barrichello]] was in second with six points, and [[Ralf Schumacher]] of the [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] team had four points. [[British American Racing]]'s (BAR) [[Jacques Villeneuve]] was fourth with three points and [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] driver [[Giancarlo Fisichella]] was fifth with two points.<ref name=points>{{cite web|title=F1 Driver's Championship Table 2000 |url=http://www.crash.net/f1/2000/championship/content.html|publisher=Crash|accessdate=13 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711102519/http://www.crash.net/f1/2000/championship/content.html |archivedate=11 July 2015 }}</ref> In the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|Constructors' Championship]] Ferrari led with a maximum amount of 16 points. Williams and BAR tied in third with four points each and Benetton were fourth on four points.<ref name=points/>\n\nPrior to the event the majority of the 11 teams conducted sessions at various locations across Europe to test their cars and new components. [[McLaren]], [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]], Williams, [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]] and [[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]] elected to test at the [[Silverstone Circuit]] in the United Kingdom from 14 to 16 March. Ferrari test driver [[Luca Badoer]] performed shakedown runs at the [[Fiorano Circuit]] in northern Italy.<ref name=FIABulletin>{{cite web|title=Formula One Update \u2013 17 March 2000|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1updt-a/17-03-00.htm|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|date=17 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001203190000/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1updt-a/17-03-00.htm|archivedate=3 December 2000|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Olivier Panis]] of the McLaren test team led on the first two days of testing; on day three, Williams' [[Jenson Button]] was the fastest driver.<ref name=FIABulletin/> The BAR, [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]], [[Sauber]] and [[Minardi]] teams did not test before the Grand Prix.<ref name=FIABulletin/>\n\n[[File:Johnny Herbert at Goodwood 2014 002.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Johnny Herbert]] ''(pictured in 2014)'' criticised the resurfacing of the race track and voiced fears of a major accident occurring.]]\n\nThe press and bookmakers considered Michael Schumacher the favourite to win the race.<ref name=\"AF1Preview\" /><ref name=GuardianBets>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Jamie|title=Odds fellow: Brazil demands a flutter on Frentzen|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A75777626/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=43b3e23f|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|page=7|via=General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In response to a statement by McLaren team principal [[Ron Dennis]]\u2014who claimed Ferrari was not as competitive as McLaren\u2014Schumacher said he was optimistic over a continuing challenge to McLaren for the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/schumacher-relaxes-as-focus-falls-on-barrichello-283435.html|title=Schumacher relaxes as focus falls on Barrichello|last=Tremayne|first=David|date=24 March 2000|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=10 May 2019|author-link=David Tremayne|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510201340/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/schumacher-relaxes-as-focus-falls-on-barrichello-283435.html|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> McLaren driver [[David Coulthard]] stated he foresaw the team starting on the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#G|grid]]'s front row and winning, after faulty seals on their [[Pneumatic valve springs|pneumatic valve systems]] forced him and two-time world champion [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] to retire from the preceding Australian Grand Prix: \"We weren't beaten fair and square in the race because we dropped out. You have to give Ferrari credit because they won when we dropped out and that's our mistake. But it means we come here believing we are competitive and still have a chance.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8992|title=Brazil: It's McLaren to beat, says Coulthard|date=23 March 2000|website=[[Autosport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510201341/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8992|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOver the month of February, the Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace was resurfaced in an attempt to reduce its bumpiness.<ref name=\"AF1Preview\" /> The pit lane exit was moved from the entry of the Senna S [[chicane]] to the Repa Opposta [[Straight (racing)|straight]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.silhouet.com/motorsport/tracks/interlag.html|title=Interlagos|date=2000|publisher=Tim Moser's Silhouette Racing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011222042457/http://www.silhouet.com/motorsport/tracks/interlag.html|archive-date=22 December 2001|url-status=live|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> A larger run-off area was installed to the outside of Laranjinha turn and its concrete barrier was padded with tyres, after [[Ricardo Zonta]] had crashed and been injured during [[1999 Brazilian Grand Prix|the 1999 race]]. [[Charlie Whiting]], the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA; Formula One's governing body) technical delegate, inspected the circuit and ordered the pit lane barriers to be moved for better driver access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/australia/s1647.html|title=FIA approves Interlagos modifications|date=22 March 2000|publisher=Formula1.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010110012100/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/australia/s1647.html|archive-date=10 January 2001|url-status=dead|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> The drivers had mixed feelings over the resurfacing work. [[Eddie Irvine]] of the Jaguar team criticised the track's condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2150.htm|title=Irvine Criticises Interlagos Track Surface|date=18 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001213222800/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2150.htm|archive-date=13 December 2000|url-status=live|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> His teammate [[Johnny Herbert]] described the bumps approaching the start/finish straight as \"horrendous\" and raised concerns over a repeat of an accident sustained by [[St\u00e9phane Sarrazin]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/coulthard-rides-out-schumachers-bumps-283404.html|title=Coulthard rides out Schumacher's bumps|last=Tremayne|first=David|date=25 March 2000|work=The Independent|access-date=10 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510201337/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/coulthard-rides-out-schumachers-bumps-283404.html|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Barrichello and his teammate Michael Schumacher, on the other hand, said the track was better for them.<ref name=FIAFriday>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil1-2000.htm|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Free Practice|date=24 March 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025180345/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil1-2000.htm|archive-date=25 October 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral teams altered their cars, either to refine their aerodynamic appendages or to solve reliability problems that emerged during the Australian Grand Prix.<ref Name=Piola>{{cite journal|last=Piola|first=Giorgio|title=Quanti interventi in casa McLaren!|journal=Autosprint|language=Italian|number=13|date=27 March \u2013 3 April 2000|pages=48\u201349}}</ref> McLaren identified an [[air filter]] failure that had the pneumatic valve system problem in the previous race, and modified its design to prevent a recurrence.<ref name=\"Piola\" /> [[Cosworth|Ford-Cosworth]] modified its engine lubrication system and the Arrows team altered the design of the [[steering linkage]].<ref name=\"Piola\" /> The FIA granted Arrows permission to enter the race after changing the design of the headrests to protect the driver in its [[Arrows A21|A21]] car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35489/1/arrows-gets-all-clear|title=Arrows gets all clear|date=22 March 2000|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103208/https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35489/1/arrows-gets-all-clear|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Practice==\nFour practice sessions were held before the Sunday race, two on Friday, and two on Saturday. The Friday morning and afternoon sessions each lasted an hour. The third and final practice sessions on Saturday morning lasted 45 minutes.<ref name=\"regulations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/regle/reg_spt/F1spt-a.htm|title=2000 Formula One Sporting Regulations|date=24 January 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000824110524/http://www.fia.com/regle/reg_spt/F1spt-a.htm|archivedate=24 August 2000|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref> The weather was hot and clear for the Friday sessions.<ref name=FIAFriday/> Barrichello made minor changes to the [[Racing setup|aerodynamic setup]] of his car before the first session,<ref name=FIAFriday/> and was fastest with a 1 minute and 17.631 seconds lap. H\u00e4kkinen, Coulthard, Michael Schumacher, Villeneuve, Prost's [[Jean Alesi]], Fisichella, [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]] of the Jordan team, Sauber driver [[Mika Salo]] and Arrows' [[Jos Verstappen]] rounded out the session's top ten drivers.<ref name=AF1FP1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2163.htm|title=Friday First Free Practice \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=24 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422045559/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2163.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> During the session, Alesi spun three times and removed the front wing on the third occurrence.<ref name=AF1FP1/> Michael Schumacher's session ended early after eight laps due to a [[Drive shaft|driveshaft]] joint leak and Zonta was restricted to four timed laps after debris accumulation overheated his engine.<ref name=FIAFriday/>\n\nWith three minutes remaining in the second Friday practice sessnion, H\u00e4kkinen bettered his 1999 [[pole position]] lap by six-tenths of a second and set the day's fastest lap of 1 minute and 15.896 seconds.<ref name=FIAFriday/> Michael Schumacher was second-fastest. Coulthard, Barrichello, [[Pedro de la Rosa]]'s Arrows, Alesi, Verstappen, Jordan's [[Jarno Trulli]], Villeneuve and Fisichella took third through tenth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2164.htm|title=Friday Second Free Practice \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=24 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092822/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2164.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> A brake and balance problem twice put Ralf Schumacher off the track. [[Alexander Wurz]] spun and beached his Benetton in a gravel trap at Mergulho corner.<ref name=FIAFriday/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3431|title=Hakkinen fastest in second free practice|date=24 March 2000|publisher=F1Racing.net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318210741/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3431|archive-date=18 March 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard spent part of the session in the pit lane as McLaren replaced his front wing after he went into the grass midway through. Verstappen tried a tyre compound  that affected his car's setup and put him into a gravel trap at the end of practice.<ref name=FIAFriday/>\n\nIt continued to be hot and dry for Saturday morning's two practice sessions.<ref name=FIASaturday>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil2-2000.htm|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Free Practice + Qualifying|date=25 March 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025190326/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil2-2000.htm|archive-date=25 August 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Teams tested different [[ride height]] setups on their cars, creating a noticeable difference in performance. They also selected the tyre compounds to use for the rest of the weekend.<ref name=F1COMSatFP>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/brazil/s1671.html|title=Saturday Practice Report \u2013 Brazil|date=25 March 2000|publisher=Formula1.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001219015300/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/brazil/s1671.html|archive-date=19 December 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard led the third practice session with a lap of 1 minute and 15.035 seconds, followed by his teammate H\u00e4kkinen, the Ferrari pair of Michael Schumacher and Barrichello, Frentzen, Fisichella, Trulli, Irvine, Minardi's [[Marc Gen\u00e9]] and Alesi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9019|title=Brazilian Grand Prix \u2013 1st Saturday practice times|date=25 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511103835/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9019|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> During the session, an engine problem for Michael Schumacher prompted his team to spend an hour and ten minutes changing it.<ref name=FIASaturday/> An oil leak in [[Gast\u00f3n Mazzacane]]'s Minardi restricted him to five timed laps, and prevented his participation in the final practice session later that day.<ref name=AF1SatFP>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2170.htm|title=Saturday Free Practice \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422032119/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2170.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHakkinen led the fourth session with a 1 minute and 14.159 seconds time on his final lap on a new set of tyres, with his teammate Coulthard third.<ref name=FIASaturday /> They were separated by Barrichello. His teammate Michael Schumacher was fourth. Trulli was fifth and Fisichella duplicated his third practice result in sixth. Villeneuve, Verstappen, Ralf Schumacher and Frentzen completed the top ten.<ref name=AF1SatFP/> Barrichello spun twice as he tested a new [[Spoiler (car)|rear wing]]. Frentzen and his teammate Trulli ran into a gravel trap and both sustained minor bodywork damage to their cars.<ref name=FIASaturday/> Zonta lost track time due to a [[Transmission (mechanics)|gearbox actuator]] fault and ran into a gravel trap.<ref name=AF1SatFP/> Button's engine failed, laying oil on the [[racing line]] between the Laranjinha and Bico do Pato corners. Salo's rear wing failed on the start/finish straight; he spun as he braked before the Senna S chicane and crashed into the wall,<ref name=FIASaturday/><ref name=F1COMSatFP/> but was unhurt.<ref name=AF1SatFP/>\n\n==Qualifying==\n[[File:Mika Haekkinen 2006.jpg|left|thumb|upright|[[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] ''(pictured in 2006)'' took the 23rd [[pole position]] of his career as a result of recording the fastest lap in qualifying.]]\n\nSaturday afternoon's one-hour qualifying session saw drivers circulate the track simultaneously. Each driver was limited to twelve laps; their fastest laps would determine the starting order for the race. During this session the [[107% rule]] was in effect, requiring each driver to remain within 107 per cent of the fastest lap to qualify for the race.<ref name=\"regulations\" /> Heavy rain fell in the session's final \u00bc hour and the resulting slippery track prevented drivers from improving their best laps.<ref name=AF1Quali>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2174.htm|title=Timothy Collings' Brazilian GP Qualifying Report|last=Collings|first=Timothy|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316044953/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2174.htm|archive-date=16 March 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> The session was [[Racing flags#Red flag|stopped]] three times because a heavy wind caused a {{Convert|6|ft|m|abbr=on}} gantry-mounted cardboard advertising [[Billboard|hoarding]], joined together by nylon ties above the start/finish straight, to detach and fall {{Convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}} onto the track.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/motorsport/694933.stm|title=FIA summon Interlagos chiefs|date=29 March 2000|publisher=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021226091122/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/motorsport/694933.stm|archive-date=26 December 2002|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/andrew-baker/2323633/Stage-set-for-chaos-at-Interlagos.html|title=Stage set for chaos at Interlagos|last=Baker|first=Andrew|date=19 October 2007|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=11 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201256/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/andrew-baker/2323633/Stage-set-for-chaos-at-Interlagos.html|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> H\u00e4kkinen went fastest with 15 minutes to go before the rain fell with a 1-minute and 14.111 seconds lap,<ref name=AF1Quali/><ref name=\"AF1BrazilGPQ\" /> earning his second consecutive pole position,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A79604882/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=9e4e0bb1|title=Button sparkles in Sao Paulo as McLaren grab front-row spots|last=Gates|first=Mark|date=26 March 2000|work=[[Sunday Herald]]|access-date=11 May 2019|page=15|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref> his third in Brazil and the 23rd of his career.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2172.htm|title=Qualifying \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316053912/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2172.htm|archive-date=16 March 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> H\u00e4kkinen's teammate Coulthard was second and the Ferrari duo of Michael Schumacher and Barrichello took third and fourth;<ref name=\"AF1Quali\" /><ref name=SVQuali>{{Cite web|url=http://www.speedvision.com/pub/articles/racing/01formula1/000325b.html|title=Hakkinen Takes Pole in Bizarre Session|last=Gardner|first=John|date=25 March 2000|publisher=[[Speed (American cable network)|Speedvision]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000510042105/http://www.speedvision.com/pub/articles/racing/01formula1/000325b.html|archive-date=10 May 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Schumacher [[Understeer and oversteer|understeered]] into the grass on his second timed lap,<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /><ref name=AutosportQuali>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9025|title=Hakkinen tops interrupted qualifying|date=25 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201301/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9025|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> damaging his car's undertray on the corrugations of a high-mounted [[Curb|kerb]].<ref name=\"AF1SatFP\" /> He drove the spare Ferrari for the rest of qualifying.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /> Barrichello had to abort a fast lap due to the stoppage.<ref name=SVQuali/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60842112/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=e03302a9.|title=Hot Hakkinen; Motor Racing|last=Windsor|first=Peter|date=26 March 2000|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|access-date=11 May 2019|page=12|author-link=Peter Windsor|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Fisichella, fifth, praised his car's handling. Irvine in sixth was happy with his Jaguar's [[Grip (auto racing)|grip]] and balance.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ/> \n\nFrentzen qualified seventh after [[Pedro Diniz]] slowed him. Zonta, eighth, focused on aerodynamic setup to improve his car's handling.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"AF1BrazilGPQ\" /> Button was fourth early on before falling to ninth.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Villeneuve qualified in tenth as traffic slowed two of his timed laps and he ran onto the grass. Ralf Schumacher was the fastest driver not to qualify in the top ten after different spring rates failed to improve the setup of his chassis.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ/> Trulli spun into a gravel trap at the Bico de Peto [[Hairpin turn|hairpin]] on his first timed lap.<ref name=AutosportQuali/> He returned to the pit lane to drive the spare Jordan car; an [[electronic control unit]] fault affected its gear selection and left him 12th. Traffic slowed all of Wurz's laps and left him in 13th. [[Clutch]] issues left Verstappen in 14th.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Alesi, 15th, swerved at more than {{Convert|250|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} to avoid the falling advertising hoarding; it damaged his car's front wing.<ref name=AF1Quali/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9035|title=Alesi calls for action after lucky escape|date=25 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201259/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9035|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> De La Rosa in 16th was slowed by the rain. Car setup issues put Herbert 17th.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ/> Gen\u00e9 in 18th ventured onto the track early in the session. [[Nick Heidfeld]] used the spare Prost car to secure 19th due to a clutch failure in his race car.<ref name=\"AF1Quali\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sat.shtml|title=The Brazilian Grand Prix 2000: Team and driver comments \u2013 Saturday|date=25 March 2000|publisher=Daily F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010212101825/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sat.shtml|archive-date=12 February 2001|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Diniz in 20th had a similar rear wing failure to his teammate Salo in 22nd.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> [[Pressure regulator|Fuel pressure]] problems led Mazzacane to drive the spare Minardi car; he separated the Sauber duo in 21st.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"AF1Quali\" />\n\n===Post-qualifying===\nDuring the second stoppage, Sauber announced its withdrawal from the race, citing a lack of time in Brazil to analyse and rectify the structural integrity of the rear wings on both their cars.<ref name=SVQuali/> The team returned to their [[Hinwil]] headquarters and found the track's bumpy surface resulted in both of their cars having higher than anticipated impact loads; Salo had a failure of the lower plane on his rear wing and Diniz's failed on the upper plane.<ref name=SauberBumps>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/sauber-blame-track-for-withdrawal-337271|title=Sauber blame track for withdrawal|date=29 March 2000|work=[[Cape Argus]]|access-date=11 May 2019|agency=[[Reuters]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201301/https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/sauber-blame-track-for-withdrawal-337271|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Qualifying classification===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}} \n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|No.|Car number}} \n! scope=\"col\" | Driver \n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor \n! scope=\"col\" | Time \n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Gap|Gap to the fastest driver}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 1:14.111\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 1:14.285\n| +0.174\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:14.508\n| +0.397\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:14.636\n| +0.525\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 11\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n| [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n| 1:15.375\n| +1.264\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 7\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:15.425\n| +1.314\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n| 1:15.455\n| +1.344\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| 23\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Ricardo Zonta]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:15.484\n| +1.373\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| 10\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Jenson Button]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:15.490\n| +1.379\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 22\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:15.515\n| +1.404\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:15.561\n| +1.450\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| 6\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Jarno Trulli]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n| 1:15.627\n| +1.516\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| 12\n| {{flagicon|Austria}} [[Alexander Wurz]]\n| [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n| 1:15.664\n| +1.553\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| 19\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Jos Verstappen]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Supertec]]\n| 1:15.704\n| +1.593\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| 14\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[Jean Alesi]]\n| [[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 1:15.715\n| +1.604\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| 18\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pedro de la Rosa]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Supertec]]\n| 1:16.002\n| +1.891\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| 8\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Johnny Herbert]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:16.250\n| +2.139\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| 20\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Marc Gen\u00e9]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 1:16.380\n| +2.269\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| 15\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n| [[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 1:17.112\n| +3.001\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20*\n| 16\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Pedro Diniz]]\n| [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:17.178\n|  +3.067{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 21\n| 21\n| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Gast\u00f3n Mazzacane]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 1:17.512\n| +3.401\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 22*\n| 17\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n| [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:18.703\n|  +4.592{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |[[107% time]]: 1:19.299\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |Source:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/qualification.aspx|title=Brazil 2000 \u2013 Qualifications|publisher=Stats F1|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114224142/http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/qualification.aspx|archive-date=14 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=14 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=ESPNResults/>\n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n\n* {{note|1|1}}{{snd}}Sauber withdrew [[Pedro Diniz]] and [[Mika Salo]] on the grounds of safety due to separate [[Spoiler (car)|rear wing]] failures on their cars.<ref name=SauberBumps/>\n\n==Warm-up==\n\nA 30-minute warm-up session was held on Sunday morning in hot and overcast weather.<ref name=FIAWarmUp>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil3-2000.htm|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Warm-Up|date=26 March 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025192224/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil3-2000.htm|archive-date=25 October 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> All drivers fine-tuned their race set-ups and drove in their [[Glossary of motorsport terms#S|spare cars]].<ref name=FIAWarmUp/> H\u00e4kkinen set the session's fastest lap at 1 minute and 16.343 seconds, ahead of Michael Schumacher, Coulthard, Barrichello, Verstappen, Ralf Schumacher, Gen\u00e9, Fisichella and Zonta in positions two to ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2183.htm|title=Sunday Warm-Up \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=26 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092357/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2183.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Ten minutes in,<ref name=F1NetWarmUp>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3549|title=Hakkinen on top before race|date=26 March 2000|publisher=F1Racing.net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318214815/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3549|archive-date=18 March 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Wurz [[Stall (engine)|stalled]] his car at the exit of the pit lane, and the session was stopped. He required the spare [[Benetton B200]] car for the rest of the session.<ref name=FIAWarmUp/> Alesi's engine failed and he switched to the spare [[Prost AP03]], which had a rear wing failure on the bumpy start/finish straight, and caused a second stoppage.<ref name=FIAWarmUp/><ref name=F1NetWarmUp/>\n\nAfter the warm-up session, and before the race, Prost examined Alesi's rear wing and found that its failure was due to older bodywork parts fitted to his car and readied its spare chassis if required. The team stated they were unconcerned over the safety of their drivers and confirmed their participation in the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8514|title=Prost to enter Brazilian GP|date=26 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103212/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8514|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Race==\nThe race began at 14:00 local time.<ref name=\"GF1Race\">{{cite web|title=Report: Michael Wins Again!|url=http://dbs.galeforcef1.com/event_report.asp?n=2000032622h10&s=2000&e=02|publisher=Gale Force F1|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503010450/http://dbs.galeforcef1.com/event_report.asp?n=2000032622h10&s=2000&e=02|archivedate=3 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The weather at the start was hot and dry with the ambient temperature {{Convert|22|C|F|abbr=}}, the track temperature {{Convert|35|C|F|abbr=}}, and the humidity at 76 per cent.<ref name=\"GF1Race\" /><ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\">{{cite web|title=2000: Round 2 \u2013 Brazil: Interlagos|url=http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews00/brazil/race.html|publisher=Formula1.com|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010210201517/http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews00/brazil/race.html|archivedate=10 February 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> Approximately 72,000 spectators attended the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60969592/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=014ffc19|title=Motor racing: Schumacher's Title Warning|last=Gordon|first=Ian|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The News Letter]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=23|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On the [[Parade lap|formation lap]], Wurz stalled his engine,<ref name=DF1RaceQuotes>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sun.shtml|title=The Brazilian Grand Prix 2000: Team and driver comments \u2013 Sunday|date=26 March 2000|publisher=Daily F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010702070823/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sun.shtml|archive-date=2 July 2001|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> and his stationary car delayed Alesi and Herbert; both drivers took up their starting positions.<ref name=AF1Report/> Wurz began the event from the pit lane.<ref name=FIARace>{{cite web|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Race Facts and Incidents|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil4-2000.htm|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025204953/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil4-2000.htm|archivedate=25 October 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref> H\u00e4kkinen made a brisk start from the grid to lead the field going into the Senna S chicane.<ref name=MCOMRace>{{cite web|last=M. Baines|first=Stephen|title=Brazilian GP Report|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/brazilian-gp-report-2002-04-15/40163/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070618/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/brazilian-gp-report-2002-04-15/40163/|archive-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard, in second, had [[wheelspin]] and was passed by Michael Schumacher, who unsuccessfully challenged H\u00e4kkinen for the lead. Coulthard retained third as Barrichello made a slow start.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Behind them, Irvine overtook Fisichella for fifth. Verstappen moved from 14th to 11th by the conclusion of the first lap; Button dropped from 9th to 13th over the same distance.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Trulli passed Ralf Schumacher and Villeneuve to progress into tenth on the left of the circuit.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\n[[File:Giancarlo Fisichella 2012 WEC Fuji.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Giancarlo Fisichella]] ''(pictured in 2012)'' earned his first podium finish of the season in second.]]\n\nAs the first two drivers reached the start/finish line,<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> Michael Schumacher, who was close behind H\u00e4kkinen throughout lap one,<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\">{{cite web|title=Schu-master wins in Brazil|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3562|publisher=F1Racing.net|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318212739/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3562|archivedate=18 March 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> steered off the racing line to pass the latter for the lead heading into the Senna S chicane.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Barrichello [[Drafting (aerodynamics)|slipstreamed]] Coulthard on the start/finish straight and overtook him for third.<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> He then ran wide and Coulthard retook third. Barrichello retook the position by the end of lap two as Coulthard lost the use of the first three gears due to a gearbox fault and was slower in the slow-speed corners.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> At the front, Michael Schumacher extended his lead over H\u00e4kkinen to four seconds by lap four and to 15 seconds by lap 15 with a series of [[fastest lap]]s. In the meantime, Trulli passed Zonta for eighth, Button overtook Alesi for 13th and Heidfeld lost 16th to de la Rosa. Verstappen progressed from 11th to seventh by passing Villeneuve, Zonta, Frentzen and Fisichella as Alesi overtook Ralf Schumacher, Villeneuve, Zonta and Frentzen to advance to ninth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Three drivers retired from the race during this period: Wurz and Heidfeld had separate engine failures on lap seven and nine and Alesi stopped with an electrical failure at the Bico de Pato hairpin on lap 11.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\nAt the end of lap 14, Barrichello drew close to H\u00e4kkinen after the latter ran wide. He slipstreamed H\u00e4kkinen and turned left to pass him for second as he braked before the Senna S chicane to start the 15th lap.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> De la Rosa passed Herbert for 14th on that lap and Trulli overtook Irvine for fifth on lap 16.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> That lap, Villeneuve retired with a race-long gearbox problem. The Ferrari and McLaren teams employed different pit stop strategies \u2013 the Ferrari team planned for two stops whereas the McLaren squad scheduled one stop.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Michael Schumacher led by 17.6 seconds over the rest of the field when he commenced the first round of pit stops for fuel and tyres four laps later.<ref name=\"GF1Race\" /> He rejoined the track in third and Barrichello led the next two laps until his stop.<ref name=\"AutosportLapByLap\">{{cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8515|title=Brazilian Grand Prix: Lap by lap|date=26 March 2000|work=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103201/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8515|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref> On lap 21, Irvine lost control of the rear of his car entering the Bico de Pato hairpin and crashed against a tyre barrier. Six laps later, Barrichello entered the pit lane with a [[hydraulic motor]] problem that spread from the [[steering wheel]] to the throttle linkage.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=DF1RaceQuotes/> As Barrichello exited the car to retire a small fire was extinguished by his mechanics.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" />\n\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 01 (sk).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Michael Schumacher]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' took his second win of the season and 37th of his career.]]\n\nTrulli made the first of two stops from fourth at the end of the 28th lap and he emerged in seventh.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> At the front of the field, H\u00e4kkinen pulled away to lead Michael Schumacher by 12 seconds until he slowed with a loss of oil engine pressure on the 30th lap.<ref name=DF1RaceQuotes/><ref name=\"AutosportLapByLap\" /> He slowed and retired in his garage. Michael Schumacher retook the lead, with the yet-to-stop Coulthard second, Verstappen third and Fisichella fourth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Coulthard lapped to within a tenth of a second of Michael Schumacher as the latter slowed slightly due to an imbalance in all four of his tyres as Ralf Schumacher challenged Fisichella for fourth.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> On lap 32, Gen\u00e9 retired from eleventh with an engine failure.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Verstappen and his teammate de la Rosa made their first pit stops on laps 35 and 37. Four laps later, Frentzen was the first driver on a one-stop strategy to enter the pit lane.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Coulthard made his only stop on lap 43 and remained in second position. Michael Schumacher led by 48 seconds when he made his second pit stop on the 51st lap and retained the lead.<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> On the same lap, Fisichella made his only stop and kept third place.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\nOn lap 51, Herbert retired in the pit lane with a gearbox failure.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> De la Rosa lost concentration and went into a gravel trap four laps later. He rejoined without losing position.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> Button battled Verstappen and overtook him for seventh on the 56th lap as Trulli made a pit stop from fourth and rejoined the track in fifth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> From the 59th lap, Coulthard began to gain on Michael Schumacher, who slowed due to an [[oil pressure]] problem.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /><ref name=\"FIARace\" /> He could not draw close enough to pass, and Schumacher took his second victory of the season, his third in Brazil and the 37th of his career in a time of 1 hour, 31 minutes and 35.271 seconds at an average speed of {{Convert|200.404|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} over a distance of {{Convert|305.939|km|mi|abbr=on}} and 71 laps.<ref name=\"CF1Brazil2000\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/27/sports/plus-auto-racing-brazilian-grand-prix-schumacher-wins.html|title=Plus: Auto Racing \u2013 Brazilian Grand Prix; Schumacher Wins|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=12 May 2019|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512111105/https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/27/sports/plus-auto-racing-brazilian-grand-prix-schumacher-wins.html|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CollingsReport>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2186.htm|title=Timothy Collings' Brazilian GP Race Report|last=Collings|first=Timothy|date=26 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092838/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2186.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard followed 4.302 seconds later and Fisichella took third. Frentzen finished fourth, Trulli fifth and Ralf Schumacher sixth. Button, Verstappen, de la Rosa, Zonta and Mazzacane were the final finishers.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> The attrition rate was high; only 11 of the 20 starters finished the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60827984/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=9e4e0bb1|title=Triumphant Schumacher travels light; Motor Racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=40|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Post-race===\nThe top three drivers appeared on the podium to collect their trophies and spoke to the media in a later press conference.<ref name=\"regulations\" /> Michael Schumacher stated that pit stop strategy helped him to win the race: \"In the past, as you may remember, we could not overtake the McLaren entries, regardless of their strategy. Now we are looking a lot more competitive \u2013 which is where we wanted to be \u2013 and the season could hardly have started better than it has.\"<ref name=PressConf>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2191.htm|title=Post-Race Press Conference \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422093049/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2191.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard said his second-place finish provided him the start to his championship campaign after his gearbox problems: \"It must have been entertaining for those who had places to watch at the first corner. Given the circumstances, I am very happy with my six points.\"<ref name=PressConf/> Fisichella revealed that his car had understeer and oversteer for the first 15 laps until its grip and balance improved. Nonetheless, he said he was pleased to finish third, \"This is a great result and will help us to be even more competitive in the future. I am confident about the next race, when we will have some new aerodynamic parts.\"<ref name=PressConf/>\n\n[[File:David Coulthard 2007.jpg|thumb|upright|[[David Coulthard]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' was disqualified from second place due to an illegal front wing endplate on his car.]]\n\nAll of the top six finishers, except for Fisichella, were found to have excess wear on the wooden planks underneath their cars. The Ferrari, McLaren, Jordan and Williams teams filed a successful appeal against the regulation concerning illegal plank wear on the basis the bumpy racing surface caused it. All four teams were reinstated after a second inspection caused a {{frac|3|1|2}} hour delay.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8531|title=Schumacher cleared as race winner|date=27 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152054/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8531|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> During the inspection, the front wing endplates on Coulthard's car were found to be {{Convert|43|mm|cm|abbr=on}} above the ground and not {{Convert|50|mm|cm|abbr=on}} as stated in the regulations''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A75778273/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=6c8d1e8c|title=Motor Racing: McLaren 'were leant on': Team allege threats made to impound car if they did not toe line over disqualification|last=Henry|first=Alan|author-link=Alan Henry|date=28 March 2000|work=The Guardian|access-date=12 May 2019|page=9|via=General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2193.htm|title=Coulthard's car bumps him from 2nd spot|date=27 March 2000|work=Cape Argus|access-date=12 May 2019|agency=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230427/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2193.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Jo Bauer]], the FIA technical delegate, deemed this to have provided Coulthard with a competitive aerodynamic advantage and the stewards disqualified the driver six hours after the race. The technical director of McLaren [[Adrian Newey]] rejected an offer from the stewards to transport Coulthard's car to Paris for a fair hearing and agreed to a set of four measurements in S\u00e3o Paulo. McLaren then filed an appeal and stated the car's undertray and chassis was damaged and shifted by vibrations from the bumps on the racing surface.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60842541/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=08dcf78c|title=Coulthard left on wing and prayer; Motor racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=28 March 2000|work=The Times|access-date=12 May 2019|page=37|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 4 April, the appeal was heard by a five-man panel at a meeting of the FIA International Court of Appeal in Paris. They rejected McLaren's appeal during the 90-minute hearing and declared the result of the race final.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A103703782/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=4dd64b01|title=Coulthard loses appeal|last=Gowar|first=Rex|date=5 April 2000|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=066|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThis promoted every driver behind Coulthard one position; Button was reclassified sixth and became the [[List of Formula One driver records#Youngest drivers to score points|youngest driver to score a Formula One World Championship point]] at the age of 20 years, 2 months and 7 days old, breaking [[Ricardo Rodr\u00edguez (racing driver)|Ricardo Rodr\u00edguez]]'s record from the [[1962 Belgian Grand Prix]].{{#tag:ref|{{As of|2020}}, the record for the youngest driver to score a Formula One World Championship point is currently held by [[Max Verstappen]], who was 17 years and 166 days old when he finished seventh at the [[2015 Malaysian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Max Verstappen makes F1 history as youngest in points|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/motor/formula1/2015/03/29/max-verstappen-makes-f1-history-as-youngest-in-points/70625740/|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=Associated Press|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=\"n\"}}<ref>{{Cite journal|date=May 2000|title=Button Makes History|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/may-2000/5/button-makes-history|journal=[[Motor Sport (magazine)|Motor Sport]]|volume=LXXVI|pages=5|access-date=12 May 2019|number=5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152047/https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/may-2000/5/button-makes-history|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/22058/9429909/f1-records-dont-approve|title=F1 records showing their age|last=Esler|first=William|date=21 August 2014|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826050137/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/22058/9429909/f1-records-dont-approve|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> On 6 April, the organisers of the Brazilian Grand Prix were summoned to a meeting of the FIA General Assembly. They were fined $100,000 for the track's safety issues and for the three times qualifying was stopped due to falling advertising hoardings. The governing body ruled it as \"exceptional circumstances\" and allowed the track to remain as part of the series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/motorsport/2000/0407/148843-formula1/|title=Formula 1: FIA fine Brazilian GP organisers|date=7 April 2000|access-date=12 May 2019|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152051/https://www.rte.ie/sport/motorsport/2000/0407/148843-formula1/|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The president of the FIA [[Max Mosley]] said an increased fine or cancelling the race was not imposed because its organisers had submitted evidence to prevent either action from occurring, \"Bearing in mind that we allowed the Brazilian promoters to place the signs there \u2013 and they probably didn't know what potential there was for the failures which occurred \u2013 it seemed only fair to impose the comparatively modest penalty.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35623/1/interlagos-bumps-a-part-of-f1-says-max|title=Interlagos bumps a part of F1, says Max|date=9 April 2000|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152050/https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35623/1/interlagos-bumps-a-part-of-f1-says-max|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nH\u00e4kkinen spoke of his disappointment over retiring from the lead of the race, \"Nothing can describe how I feel, We have been quick all weekend, right the way through, so I am not happy to be leaving Brazil without any points. We have some work to do before the start of the European season.\"<ref name=CollingsReport/> Button was quoted in the press as stating his preference to score points on the track and not be awarded them in a court of appeal, \"I heard the news about David as I was making my way to the airport to fly back from Brazil \u2013 and I can't say it gave me any great feeling of joy. You want to earn any success through your driving skills, not someone else's misfortune.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9043|title=Button prefers to make point in races|date=29 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152050/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9043|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> [[Eddie Jordan]], the owner of the Jordan team, said that both his cars finishing the event demonstrated they could last a full race distance after retiring from the Australian Grand Prix with mechanical issues. Frentzen stated it was as if the team's season had commenced in Brazil and the team still required maintenance to improve their performance, \"But we are a very strong team with a good atmosphere, I get along well with Jarno and everything is fine so far.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2188.htm|title=Jordan Back in the Points in Brazil|last=Milliken|first=Mary|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422035436/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2188.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe gap in the Drivers' Championship after the race stood at 12 points in favour of Michael Schumacher with Fisichella moving from fifth to second as a result of his second-place finish. Barrichello dropped to third and Ralf Schumacher fell to fourth. Frentzen rounded out the top five.<ref name=\"points\" /> In the Constructors' Championship, Ferrari moved further ahead with 26 points and the Benetton team progressed from fourth to second. Jordan's first points of the season put them third while Williams and BAR were fourth and fifth with fifteen races left in the season.<ref name=\"points\" />\n\n===Race classification===\nDrivers who scored [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|championship points]] are denoted in '''bold'''.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|No.|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Laps|Laps completed}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Time/Retired\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Grid|Final grid positions}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| 3\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} '''[[Michael Schumacher]]'''\n|'''[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]'''\n| 71\n| 1:31:35.271\n| 3\n|'''10'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| 11\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} '''[[Giancarlo Fisichella]]'''\n|'''[[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]'''\n| 71\n|  +39.898\n| 5\n|'''6'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| 5\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} '''[[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]'''\n|'''[[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]'''\n| 71\n|  +42.268\n| 7\n|'''4'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| 6\n|{{flagicon|Italy}} '''[[Jarno Trulli]]'''\n|'''[[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]'''\n| 71\n|  +1:12.780\n| 12\n|'''3'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 9\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} '''[[Ralf Schumacher]]'''\n|'''[[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]'''\n| 70\n|  +1 Lap\n| 11\n|'''2'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 10\n|{{flagicon|UK}} '''[[Jenson Button]]'''\n|'''[[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]'''\n| 70\n|  +1 Lap\n| 9\n|'''1'''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 19\n|{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Jos Verstappen]]\n|[[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Supertec]]\n| 70\n|  +1 Lap\n| 14\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| 18\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pedro de la Rosa]]\n|[[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Supertec]]\n| 70\n|  +1 Lap\n| 16\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| 23\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Ricardo Zonta]]\n|[[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 69\n|  +2 Laps\n| 8\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 21\n|{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Gast\u00f3n Mazzacane]]\n|[[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 69\n|  +2 Laps\n| 20\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 8\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Johnny Herbert]]\n|[[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 51\n| Gearbox\n| 17\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 20\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Marc Gen\u00e9]]\n|[[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 31\n| Engine\n| 18\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 1\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]]\n|[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 30\n| Oil pressure\n| 1\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 4\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n|[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 27\n| Hydraulics\n| 4\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 7\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n|[[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 20\n| Spun off\n| 6\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 22\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n|[[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 16\n| Gearbox\n| 10\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 14\n|{{flagicon|France}} [[Jean Alesi]]\n|[[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 11\n| Electrical\n| 15\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 15\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n|[[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 9\n| Engine\n| 19\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 12\n|{{flagicon|Austria}} [[Alexander Wurz]]\n|[[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n| 6\n| Engine\n| 13\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | DSQ\n| 2\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n|[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 71\n| Illegal front wing endplates (+4.302)\n| 2\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | DNS\n| 16\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Pedro Diniz]]\n|[[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 0\n| Safety concerns\n| 0\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | DNS\n| 17\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n|[[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 0\n| Safety concerns\n| 0\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |{{center|Source:<ref name=ESPNResults>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/f1/motorsport/race/2036.html?|title=2000 Brazilian Grand Prix results|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=13 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113140123/http://en.espn.co.uk/f1/motorsport/race/2036.html|archivedate=13 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"formula1.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.formula1.com/results/season/2000/52/ |title=2000 Brazilian Grand Prix |publisher=Formula One |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010081255/http://www.formula1.com/results/season/2000/52/ |archivedate=10 October 2014 |accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Championship standings after the race==\nNote, only the top five positions are included for both sets of standings.\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Drivers' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 20\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| align=\"right\"| 6\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 6\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n| align=\"right\"| 4\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=points/><ref name=\"champ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/championnat.aspx|title=Brazil 2000 \u2013 Championship|publisher=Stats F1|access-date=13 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717211930/http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/championnat.aspx|archive-date=17 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n;Constructors' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| align=\"right\"| 26\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]] <!--Benetton raced under an Italian racing licence from 1997 onwards, so must be recorded as Italian here. Thanks.--->\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|IRE}} [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n| align=\"right\"| 7\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| align=\"right\"| 7\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| align=\"right\"| 4\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=points/><ref name=\"champ\"/>\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{F1 race report\n| Name_of_race            = [[Brazilian Grand Prix]] \n| Year_of_race            = 2000\n| Previous_race_in_season = [[2000 Australian Grand Prix]]\n| Next_race_in_season     = [[2000 San Marino Grand Prix]]\n| Previous_year's_race    = [[1999 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n| Next_year's_race        = [[2001 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n}}\n{{F1GP 00-09}}\n{{Portal bar|Brazil|Sports|Formula One}}\n\n{{coord|23|42|13|S|46|41|59|W|source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2000 Formula One races|Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:2000 in Brazilian motorsport|Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:March 2000 sports events in South America|Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox Grand Prix race report\n|Type           = F1\n|Country        = Brazil\n|Grand Prix     = Brazilian\n|Date           = 26 March\n|Year           = 2000\n|Image          = Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace (AKA Interlagos) track map.svg\n|Caption        =\n|Details ref    = <ref name=CF1Brazil2000>{{cite web|title=2000 Brazilian GP: XXIX Grande Pr\u00eamio Marlboro do Brasil|url=http://www.chicanef1.com/racetit.pl?year=2000&gp=Brazilian%20GP|publisher=Chicane F1|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209211055/http://www.chicanef1.com/racetit.pl?year=2000&gp=Brazilian%20GP|archivedate=9 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=AF1Report>{{cite journal|last=Lupini|first=Michele|title=The Brazilian GP Review|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/lupini.html|work=Atlas F1|volume=6|number=13|date=29 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000822102241/http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/lupini.html|archivedate=22 August 2000|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=GPCOMBrazil00>{{cite web|title=Grand Prix Results: Brazilian GP, 2000|url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr648.html|publisher=GrandPrix.com|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020102025837/http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr648.html|archivedate=2 January 2002|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|Race_No        = 2\n|Season_No      = 17\n|Official name  = XXIX Grande Pr\u00eamio Marlboro do Brasil\n|Location       = [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil\n|Course         = Permanent racing facility\n|Course_mi      = 2.677\n|Course_km      = 4.309\n|Distance_laps  = 71\n|Distance_mi    = 190.681\n|Distance_km    = 305.939 \n|Attendance     = 72,000\n|Weather        = Sunny, Air: {{convert|22|C|F}}, Track: {{convert|35|C|F}}\n|Pole_Driver    = [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]]\n|Pole_Team      = [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n|Pole_Time      = 1:14.111\n|Pole_Country   = Finland\n|Fast_Driver    = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|Fast_Team      = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|Fast_Time      = 1:14.755\n|Fast_Lap       = 48\n|Fast_Country   = Germany\n|First_Driver   = [[Michael Schumacher]]\n|First_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|First_Country  = Germany\n|Second_Driver  = [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n|Second_Team    = [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n|Second_Country = Italy\n|Third_Driver   = [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n|Third_Team     = [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n|Third_Country  = Germany\n|Lapchart       = {{F1Laps2000|BRA}}\n}}\nThe '''2000 Brazilian Grand Prix''' (officially the '''XXIX Grande Pr\u00eamio Marlboro do Brasil''') was a [[Formula One]] motor race held on 26 March 2000 at the [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]] in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil. 72,000 people attended the race, which was the second round of the [[2000 Formula One World Championship]] and the 29th overall edition of the [[Brazilian Grand Prix|event]]. [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] won the 71-lap race from a third-position start. [[Giancarlo Fisichella]] of the [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] team finished in second and [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]'s [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]] was third.\n\n[[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] of the [[McLaren]] team took [[pole position]] by recording the fastest lap in qualifying. He led on the first lap of the race before Michael Schumacher passed him at the start of lap two. Thereafter, Michael Schumacher opened up a 17.6 second lead before his first of two [[pit stop]]s for fuel and tyres on lap 20. He retook the lead after H\u00e4kkinen retired with a loss of engine oil pressure ten laps later. [[David Coulthard]] in the other McLaren gained on Michael Schumacher in the final 12 laps as the latter slowed to manage an [[oil pressure]] problem. He was not close enough to make a pass for the win and Michael Schumacher took his second consecutive victory of the season, his third in Brazil and the 37th of his career.\n\nAfter the race, Coulthard was disqualified from second place due to an illegal front wing endplate. McLaren filed an appeal to the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]'s International Court of Appeal, which was rejected. The disqualification advanced every driver behind Coulthard by a single position. The result extended Michael Schumacher's lead atop the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Drivers' Championship]] to 12 [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]]. Fisichella moved from fifth to second as [[Rubens Barrichello]] in the second Ferrari fell to third after not finishing the race. Ferrari further increased their lead in the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|Constructors' Championship]] to 18 points as Benetton advanced to second with fifteen races left in the season.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace, July 3, 2018 SkySat (cropped).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]] ''(pictured in 2018)'', where the race was held.]]\nThe 2000 [[Brazilian Grand Prix]] was the second of the 17 motor races in the [[2000 Formula One World Championship]] and the 29th overall edition of the event. It took place at the 15-turn {{convert|4.309|km|mi|abbr=on}} [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]] in the Brazilian city of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] on 26 March.<ref name=CF1Brazil2000/><ref name=AF1Preview/> The high-altitude, anti-clockwise track had significant elevation changes, placing a heavy load of [[g-force]] on the left-hand side of drivers' necks. Teams altered their cars to run at medium to high levels of [[downforce]] and the [[Damper (flow)|dampers]], [[Coil spring|springs]] and [[Suspension (vehicle)|suspensions]] were optimised to adapt to the bumpy track surface.<ref name=\"AF1Preview\" /> Formula One's control [[Formula One tyre|tyre]] supplier [[Bridgestone]] brought the soft and the medium dry compound tyres to the race.<ref name=AF1Preview>{{cite journal|last=Tytler|first=Ewan|title=The Brazilian GP Preview|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/preview/tytler.html|journal=Atlas F1|volume=6|number=12|date=22 March 2000|accessdate=31 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000510041938/http://www.atlasf1.com/2000/bra/preview/tytler.html|archivedate=10 May 2000}}</ref>\n\nAfter winning the preceding [[2000 Australian Grand Prix|Australian Grand Prix]]\u2014the first of the 17 World Championship races\u2014[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] driver [[Michael Schumacher]] led the [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Drivers' Championship]] with ten [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|points]]; his teammate [[Rubens Barrichello]] was in second with six points, and [[Ralf Schumacher]] of the [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]] team had four points. [[British American Racing]]'s (BAR) [[Jacques Villeneuve]] was fourth with three points and [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] driver [[Giancarlo Fisichella]] was fifth with two points.<ref name=points>{{cite web|title=F1 Driver's Championship Table 2000 |url=http://www.crash.net/f1/2000/championship/content.html|publisher=Crash|accessdate=13 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711102519/http://www.crash.net/f1/2000/championship/content.html |archivedate=11 July 2015 }}</ref> In the [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|Constructors' Championship]] Ferrari led with a maximum amount of 16 points. Williams and BAR tied in third with four points each and Benetton were fourth on four points.<ref name=points/>\n\nPrior to the event the majority of the 11 teams conducted sessions at various locations across Europe to test their cars and new components. [[McLaren]], [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]], Williams, [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]] and [[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]] elected to test at the [[Silverstone Circuit]] in the United Kingdom from 14 to 16 March. Ferrari test driver [[Luca Badoer]] performed shakedown runs at the [[Fiorano Circuit]] in northern Italy.<ref name=FIABulletin>{{cite web|title=Formula One Update \u2013 17 March 2000|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1updt-a/17-03-00.htm|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|date=17 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001203190000/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1updt-a/17-03-00.htm|archivedate=3 December 2000|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Olivier Panis]] of the McLaren test team led on the first two days of testing; on day three, Williams' [[Jenson Button]] was the fastest driver.<ref name=FIABulletin/> The BAR, [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]], [[Sauber]] and [[Minardi]] teams did not test before the Grand Prix.<ref name=FIABulletin/>\n\n[[File:Johnny Herbert at Goodwood 2014 002.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Johnny Herbert]] ''(pictured in 2014)'' criticised the resurfacing of the race track and voiced fears of a major accident occurring.]]\n\nThe press and bookmakers considered Michael Schumacher the favourite to win the race.<ref name=\"AF1Preview\" /><ref name=GuardianBets>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Jamie|title=Odds fellow: Brazil demands a flutter on Frentzen|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A75777626/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=43b3e23f|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|page=7|via=General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In response to a statement by McLaren team principal [[Ron Dennis]]\u2014who claimed Ferrari was not as competitive as McLaren\u2014Schumacher said he was optimistic over a continuing challenge to McLaren for the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/schumacher-relaxes-as-focus-falls-on-barrichello-283435.html|title=Schumacher relaxes as focus falls on Barrichello|last=Tremayne|first=David|date=24 March 2000|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=10 May 2019|author-link=David Tremayne|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510201340/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/schumacher-relaxes-as-focus-falls-on-barrichello-283435.html|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> McLaren driver [[David Coulthard]] stated he foresaw the team starting on the [[Glossary of motorsport terms#G|grid]]'s front row and winning, after faulty seals on their [[Pneumatic valve springs|pneumatic valve systems]] forced him and two-time world champion [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] to retire from the preceding Australian Grand Prix: \"We weren't beaten fair and square in the race because we dropped out. You have to give Ferrari credit because they won when we dropped out and that's our mistake. But it means we come here believing we are competitive and still have a chance.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8992|title=Brazil: It's McLaren to beat, says Coulthard|date=23 March 2000|website=[[Autosport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510201341/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8992|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOver the month of February, the Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace was resurfaced in an attempt to reduce its bumpiness.<ref name=\"AF1Preview\" /> The pit lane exit was moved from the entry of the Senna S [[chicane]] to the Repa Opposta [[Straight (racing)|straight]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.silhouet.com/motorsport/tracks/interlag.html|title=Interlagos|date=2000|publisher=Tim Moser's Silhouette Racing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20011222042457/http://www.silhouet.com/motorsport/tracks/interlag.html|archive-date=22 December 2001|url-status=live|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> A larger run-off area was installed to the outside of Laranjinha turn and its concrete barrier was padded with tyres, after [[Ricardo Zonta]] had crashed and been injured during [[1999 Brazilian Grand Prix|the 1999 race]]. [[Charlie Whiting]], the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA; Formula One's governing body) technical delegate, inspected the circuit and ordered the pit lane barriers to be moved for better driver access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/australia/s1647.html|title=FIA approves Interlagos modifications|date=22 March 2000|publisher=Formula1.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010110012100/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/australia/s1647.html|archive-date=10 January 2001|url-status=dead|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> The drivers had mixed feelings over the resurfacing work. [[Eddie Irvine]] of the Jaguar team criticised the track's condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2150.htm|title=Irvine Criticises Interlagos Track Surface|date=18 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001213222800/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2150.htm|archive-date=13 December 2000|url-status=live|access-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> His teammate [[Johnny Herbert]] described the bumps approaching the start/finish straight as \"horrendous\" and raised concerns over a repeat of an accident sustained by [[St\u00e9phane Sarrazin]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/coulthard-rides-out-schumachers-bumps-283404.html|title=Coulthard rides out Schumacher's bumps|last=Tremayne|first=David|date=25 March 2000|work=The Independent|access-date=10 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510201337/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/coulthard-rides-out-schumachers-bumps-283404.html|archive-date=10 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Barrichello and his teammate Michael Schumacher, on the other hand, said the track was better for them.<ref name=FIAFriday>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil1-2000.htm|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Free Practice|date=24 March 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025180345/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil1-2000.htm|archive-date=25 October 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral teams altered their cars, either to refine their aerodynamic appendages or to solve reliability problems that emerged during the Australian Grand Prix.<ref Name=Piola>{{cite journal|last=Piola|first=Giorgio|title=Quanti interventi in casa McLaren!|journal=Autosprint|language=Italian|number=13|date=27 March \u2013 3 April 2000|pages=48\u201349}}</ref> McLaren identified an [[air filter]] failure that had the pneumatic valve system problem in the previous race, and modified its design to prevent a recurrence.<ref name=\"Piola\" /> [[Cosworth|Ford-Cosworth]] modified its engine lubrication system and the Arrows team altered the design of the [[steering linkage]].<ref name=\"Piola\" /> The FIA granted Arrows permission to enter the race after changing the design of the headrests to protect the driver in its [[Arrows A21|A21]] car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35489/1/arrows-gets-all-clear|title=Arrows gets all clear|date=22 March 2000|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103208/https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35489/1/arrows-gets-all-clear|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Practice==\nFour practice sessions were held before the Sunday race, two on Friday, and two on Saturday. The Friday morning and afternoon sessions each lasted an hour. The third and final practice sessions on Saturday morning lasted 45 minutes.<ref name=\"regulations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/regle/reg_spt/F1spt-a.htm|title=2000 Formula One Sporting Regulations|date=24 January 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000824110524/http://www.fia.com/regle/reg_spt/F1spt-a.htm|archivedate=24 August 2000|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref> The weather was hot and clear for the Friday sessions.<ref name=FIAFriday/> Barrichello made minor changes to the [[Racing setup|aerodynamic setup]] of his car before the first session,<ref name=FIAFriday/> and was fastest with a 1 minute and 17.631 seconds lap. H\u00e4kkinen, Coulthard, Michael Schumacher, Villeneuve, Prost's [[Jean Alesi]], Fisichella, [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]] of the Jordan team, Sauber driver [[Mika Salo]] and Arrows' [[Jos Verstappen]] rounded out the session's top ten drivers.<ref name=AF1FP1>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2163.htm|title=Friday First Free Practice \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=24 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422045559/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2163.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> During the session, Alesi spun three times and removed the front wing on the third occurrence.<ref name=AF1FP1/> Michael Schumacher's session ended early after eight laps due to a [[Drive shaft|driveshaft]] joint leak and Zonta was restricted to four timed laps after debris accumulation overheated his engine.<ref name=FIAFriday/>\n\nWith three minutes remaining in the second Friday practice sessnion, H\u00e4kkinen bettered his 1999 [[pole position]] lap by six-tenths of a second and set the day's fastest lap of 1 minute and 15.896 seconds.<ref name=FIAFriday/> Michael Schumacher was second-fastest. Coulthard, Barrichello, [[Pedro de la Rosa]]'s Arrows, Alesi, Verstappen, Jordan's [[Jarno Trulli]], Villeneuve and Fisichella took third through tenth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2164.htm|title=Friday Second Free Practice \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=24 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092822/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2164.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> A brake and balance problem twice put Ralf Schumacher off the track. [[Alexander Wurz]] spun and beached his Benetton in a gravel trap at Mergulho corner.<ref name=FIAFriday/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3431|title=Hakkinen fastest in second free practice|date=24 March 2000|publisher=F1Racing.net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318210741/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3431|archive-date=18 March 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard spent part of the session in the pit lane as McLaren replaced his front wing after he went into the grass midway through. Verstappen tried a tyre compound  that affected his car's setup and put him into a gravel trap at the end of practice.<ref name=FIAFriday/>\n\nIt continued to be hot and dry for Saturday morning's two practice sessions.<ref name=FIASaturday>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil2-2000.htm|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Free Practice + Qualifying|date=25 March 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025190326/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil2-2000.htm|archive-date=25 August 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Teams tested different [[ride height]] setups on their cars, creating a noticeable difference in performance. They also selected the tyre compounds to use for the rest of the weekend.<ref name=F1COMSatFP>{{Cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/brazil/s1671.html|title=Saturday Practice Report \u2013 Brazil|date=25 March 2000|publisher=Formula1.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001219015300/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines00/brazil/s1671.html|archive-date=19 December 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard led the third practice session with a lap of 1 minute and 15.035 seconds, followed by his teammate H\u00e4kkinen, the Ferrari pair of Michael Schumacher and Barrichello, Frentzen, Fisichella, Trulli, Irvine, Minardi's [[Marc Gen\u00e9]] and Alesi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9019|title=Brazilian Grand Prix \u2013 1st Saturday practice times|date=25 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511103835/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9019|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> During the session, an engine problem for Michael Schumacher prompted his team to spend an hour and ten minutes changing it.<ref name=FIASaturday/> An oil leak in [[Gast\u00f3n Mazzacane]]'s Minardi restricted him to five timed laps, and prevented his participation in the final practice session later that day.<ref name=AF1SatFP>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2170.htm|title=Saturday Free Practice \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422032119/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2170.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHakkinen led the fourth session with a 1 minute and 14.159 seconds time on his final lap on a new set of tyres, with his teammate Coulthard third.<ref name=FIASaturday /> They were separated by Barrichello. His teammate Michael Schumacher was fourth. Trulli was fifth and Fisichella duplicated his third practice result in sixth. Villeneuve, Verstappen, Ralf Schumacher and Frentzen completed the top ten.<ref name=AF1SatFP/> Barrichello spun twice as he tested a new [[Spoiler (car)|rear wing]]. Frentzen and his teammate Trulli ran into a gravel trap and both sustained minor bodywork damage to their cars.<ref name=FIASaturday/> Zonta lost track time due to a [[Transmission (mechanics)|gearbox actuator]] fault and ran into a gravel trap.<ref name=AF1SatFP/> Button's engine failed, laying oil on the [[racing line]] between the Laranjinha and Bico do Pato corners. Salo's rear wing failed on the start/finish straight; he spun as he braked before the Senna S chicane and crashed into the wall,<ref name=FIASaturday/><ref name=F1COMSatFP/> but was unhurt.<ref name=AF1SatFP/>\n\n==Qualifying==\n[[File:Mika Haekkinen 2006.jpg|left|thumb|upright|[[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] ''(pictured in 2006)'' took the 23rd [[pole position]] of his career as a result of recording the fastest lap in qualifying.]]\n\nSaturday afternoon's one-hour qualifying session saw drivers circulate the track simultaneously. Each driver was limited to twelve laps; their fastest laps would determine the starting order for the race. During this session the [[107% rule]] was in effect, requiring each driver to remain within 107 per cent of the fastest lap to qualify for the race.<ref name=\"regulations\" /> Heavy rain fell in the session's final \u00bc hour and the resulting slippery track prevented drivers from improving their best laps.<ref name=AF1Quali>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2174.htm|title=Timothy Collings' Brazilian GP Qualifying Report|last=Collings|first=Timothy|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316044953/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2174.htm|archive-date=16 March 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> The session was [[Racing flags#Red flag|stopped]] three times because a heavy wind caused a {{Convert|6|ft|m|abbr=on}} gantry-mounted cardboard advertising [[Billboard|hoarding]], joined together by nylon ties above the start/finish straight, to detach and fall {{Convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}} onto the track.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/motorsport/694933.stm|title=FIA summon Interlagos chiefs|date=29 March 2000|publisher=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021226091122/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/motorsport/694933.stm|archive-date=26 December 2002|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/andrew-baker/2323633/Stage-set-for-chaos-at-Interlagos.html|title=Stage set for chaos at Interlagos|last=Baker|first=Andrew|date=19 October 2007|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=11 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201256/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/journalists/andrew-baker/2323633/Stage-set-for-chaos-at-Interlagos.html|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> H\u00e4kkinen went fastest with 15 minutes to go before the rain fell with a 1-minute and 14.111 seconds lap,<ref name=AF1Quali/><ref name=\"AF1BrazilGPQ\" /> earning his second consecutive pole position,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A79604882/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=9e4e0bb1|title=Button sparkles in Sao Paulo as McLaren grab front-row spots|last=Gates|first=Mark|date=26 March 2000|work=[[Sunday Herald]]|access-date=11 May 2019|page=15|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref> his third in Brazil and the 23rd of his career.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2172.htm|title=Qualifying \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316053912/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2172.htm|archive-date=16 March 2016|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> H\u00e4kkinen's teammate Coulthard was second and the Ferrari duo of Michael Schumacher and Barrichello took third and fourth;<ref name=\"AF1Quali\" /><ref name=SVQuali>{{Cite web|url=http://www.speedvision.com/pub/articles/racing/01formula1/000325b.html|title=Hakkinen Takes Pole in Bizarre Session|last=Gardner|first=John|date=25 March 2000|publisher=[[Speed (American cable network)|Speedvision]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000510042105/http://www.speedvision.com/pub/articles/racing/01formula1/000325b.html|archive-date=10 May 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Schumacher [[Understeer and oversteer|understeered]] into the grass on his second timed lap,<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /><ref name=AutosportQuali>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9025|title=Hakkinen tops interrupted qualifying|date=25 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201301/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9025|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> damaging his car's undertray on the corrugations of a high-mounted [[Curb|kerb]].<ref name=\"AF1SatFP\" /> He drove the spare Ferrari for the rest of qualifying.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /> Barrichello had to abort a fast lap due to the stoppage.<ref name=SVQuali/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60842112/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=e03302a9.|title=Hot Hakkinen; Motor Racing|last=Windsor|first=Peter|date=26 March 2000|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|access-date=11 May 2019|page=12|author-link=Peter Windsor|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Fisichella, fifth, praised his car's handling. Irvine in sixth was happy with his Jaguar's [[Grip (auto racing)|grip]] and balance.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ/> \n\nFrentzen qualified seventh after [[Pedro Diniz]] slowed him. Zonta, eighth, focused on aerodynamic setup to improve his car's handling.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"AF1BrazilGPQ\" /> Button was fourth early on before falling to ninth.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Villeneuve qualified in tenth as traffic slowed two of his timed laps and he ran onto the grass. Ralf Schumacher was the fastest driver not to qualify in the top ten after different spring rates failed to improve the setup of his chassis.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ/> Trulli spun into a gravel trap at the Bico de Peto [[Hairpin turn|hairpin]] on his first timed lap.<ref name=AutosportQuali/> He returned to the pit lane to drive the spare Jordan car; an [[electronic control unit]] fault affected its gear selection and left him 12th. Traffic slowed all of Wurz's laps and left him in 13th. [[Clutch]] issues left Verstappen in 14th.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Alesi, 15th, swerved at more than {{Convert|250|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} to avoid the falling advertising hoarding; it damaged his car's front wing.<ref name=AF1Quali/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9035|title=Alesi calls for action after lucky escape|date=25 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201259/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9035|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> De La Rosa in 16th was slowed by the rain. Car setup issues put Herbert 17th.<ref name=AF1BrazilGPQ/> Gen\u00e9 in 18th ventured onto the track early in the session. [[Nick Heidfeld]] used the spare Prost car to secure 19th due to a clutch failure in his race car.<ref name=\"AF1Quali\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sat.shtml|title=The Brazilian Grand Prix 2000: Team and driver comments \u2013 Saturday|date=25 March 2000|publisher=Daily F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010212101825/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sat.shtml|archive-date=12 February 2001|url-status=dead|access-date=11 May 2019}}</ref> Diniz in 20th had a similar rear wing failure to his teammate Salo in 22nd.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> [[Pressure regulator|Fuel pressure]] problems led Mazzacane to drive the spare Minardi car; he separated the Sauber duo in 21st.<ref name=\"FIASaturday\" /><ref name=\"AF1Quali\" />\n\n===Post-qualifying===\nDuring the second stoppage, Sauber announced its withdrawal from the race, citing a lack of time in Brazil to analyse and rectify the structural integrity of the rear wings on both their cars.<ref name=SVQuali/> The team returned to their [[Hinwil]] headquarters and found the track's bumpy surface resulted in both of their cars having higher than anticipated impact loads; Salo had a failure of the lower plane on his rear wing and Diniz's failed on the upper plane.<ref name=SauberBumps>{{Cite news|url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/sauber-blame-track-for-withdrawal-337271|title=Sauber blame track for withdrawal|date=29 March 2000|work=[[Cape Argus]]|access-date=11 May 2019|agency=[[Reuters]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511201301/https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/sport/sauber-blame-track-for-withdrawal-337271|archive-date=11 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Qualifying classification===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}} \n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|No.|Car number}} \n! scope=\"col\" | Driver \n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor \n! scope=\"col\" | Time \n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Gap|Gap to the fastest driver}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 1:14.111\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n| [[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 1:14.285\n| +0.174\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:14.508\n| +0.397\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 1:14.636\n| +0.525\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| 11\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n| [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n| 1:15.375\n| +1.264\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| 7\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:15.425\n| +1.314\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n| 1:15.455\n| +1.344\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| 23\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Ricardo Zonta]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:15.484\n| +1.373\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| 10\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Jenson Button]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:15.490\n| +1.379\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| 22\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n| [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 1:15.515\n| +1.404\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| 1:15.561\n| +1.450\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| 6\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Jarno Trulli]]\n| [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n| 1:15.627\n| +1.516\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| 12\n| {{flagicon|Austria}} [[Alexander Wurz]]\n| [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n| 1:15.664\n| +1.553\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| 19\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Jos Verstappen]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Supertec]]\n| 1:15.704\n| +1.593\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| 14\n| {{flagicon|France}} [[Jean Alesi]]\n| [[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 1:15.715\n| +1.604\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| 18\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pedro de la Rosa]]\n| [[Arrows Grand Prix International|Arrows]]-[[Supertec]]\n| 1:16.002\n| +1.891\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| 8\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Johnny Herbert]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:16.250\n| +2.139\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| 20\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Marc Gen\u00e9]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 1:16.380\n| +2.269\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| 15\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n| [[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 1:17.112\n| +3.001\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20*\n| 16\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Pedro Diniz]]\n| [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:17.178\n|  +3.067{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 21\n| 21\n| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Gast\u00f3n Mazzacane]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 1:17.512\n| +3.401\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 22*\n| 17\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n| [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:18.703\n|  +4.592{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |[[107% time]]: 1:19.299\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |Source:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/qualification.aspx|title=Brazil 2000 \u2013 Qualifications|publisher=Stats F1|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114224142/http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/qualification.aspx|archive-date=14 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=14 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=ESPNResults/>\n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n\n* {{note|1|1}}{{snd}}Sauber withdrew [[Pedro Diniz]] and [[Mika Salo]] on the grounds of safety due to separate [[Spoiler (car)|rear wing]] failures on their cars.<ref name=SauberBumps/>\n\n==Warm-up==\n\nA 30-minute warm-up session was held on Sunday morning in hot and overcast weather.<ref name=FIAWarmUp>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil3-2000.htm|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Warm-Up|date=26 March 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025192224/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil3-2000.htm|archive-date=25 October 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> All drivers fine-tuned their race set-ups and drove in their [[Glossary of motorsport terms#S|spare cars]].<ref name=FIAWarmUp/> H\u00e4kkinen set the session's fastest lap at 1 minute and 16.343 seconds, ahead of Michael Schumacher, Coulthard, Barrichello, Verstappen, Ralf Schumacher, Gen\u00e9, Fisichella and Zonta in positions two to ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2183.htm|title=Sunday Warm-Up \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=26 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092357/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2183.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Ten minutes in,<ref name=F1NetWarmUp>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3549|title=Hakkinen on top before race|date=26 March 2000|publisher=F1Racing.net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318214815/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3549|archive-date=18 March 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Wurz [[Stall (engine)|stalled]] his car at the exit of the pit lane, and the session was stopped. He required the spare [[Benetton B200]] car, which was setup for his teammate Fisichella.<ref name=FIAWarmUp/> Alesi's engine failed and he switched to the spare [[Prost AP03]], which had a rear wing failure on the bumpy start/finish straight, and caused a second stoppage.<ref name=FIAWarmUp/><ref name=F1NetWarmUp/>\n\nAfter the warm-up session, and before the race, Prost examined Alesi's rear wing and found that its failure was due to older bodywork parts fitted to his car and readied its spare chassis if required. The team stated they were unconcerned over the safety of their drivers and confirmed their participation in the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8514|title=Prost to enter Brazilian GP|date=26 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103212/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8514|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Race==\nThe race began at 14:00 local time.<ref name=\"GF1Race\">{{cite web|title=Report: Michael Wins Again!|url=http://dbs.galeforcef1.com/event_report.asp?n=2000032622h10&s=2000&e=02|publisher=Gale Force F1|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503010450/http://dbs.galeforcef1.com/event_report.asp?n=2000032622h10&s=2000&e=02|archivedate=3 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The weather at the start was hot and dry with the ambient temperature {{Convert|22|C|F|abbr=}}, the track temperature {{Convert|35|C|F|abbr=}}, and the humidity at 76 per cent.<ref name=\"GF1Race\" /><ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\">{{cite web|title=2000: Round 2 \u2013 Brazil: Interlagos|url=http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews00/brazil/race.html|publisher=Formula1.com|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010210201517/http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews00/brazil/race.html|archivedate=10 February 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> Approximately 72,000 spectators attended the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60969592/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=014ffc19|title=Motor racing: Schumacher's Title Warning|last=Gordon|first=Ian|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The News Letter]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=23|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On the [[Parade lap|formation lap]], Wurz stalled his engine,<ref name=DF1RaceQuotes>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sun.shtml|title=The Brazilian Grand Prix 2000: Team and driver comments \u2013 Sunday|date=26 March 2000|publisher=Daily F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010702070823/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sun.shtml|archive-date=2 July 2001|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> and his stationary car delayed Alesi and Herbert; both drivers took up their starting positions.<ref name=AF1Report/> Wurz began the event from the pit lane.<ref name=FIARace>{{cite web|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Race Facts and Incidents|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil4-2000.htm|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025204953/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil4-2000.htm|archivedate=25 October 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref> H\u00e4kkinen made a brisk start from the grid to lead the field going into the Senna S chicane.<ref name=MCOMRace>{{cite web|last=M. Baines|first=Stephen|title=Brazilian GP Report|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/brazilian-gp-report-2002-04-15/40163/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070618/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/brazilian-gp-report-2002-04-15/40163/|archive-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard, in second, had [[wheelspin]] and was passed by Michael Schumacher, who unsuccessfully challenged H\u00e4kkinen for the lead. Coulthard retained third as Barrichello made a slow start.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Behind them, Irvine overtook Fisichella for fifth. Verstappen moved from 14th to 11th by the conclusion of the first lap; Button dropped from 9th to 13th over the same distance.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Trulli passed Ralf Schumacher and Villeneuve to progress into tenth on the left of the circuit.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\n[[File:Giancarlo Fisichella 2012 WEC Fuji.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Giancarlo Fisichella]] ''(pictured in 2012)'' earned his first podium finish of the season in second.]]\n\nAs the first two drivers reached the start/finish line,<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> Michael Schumacher, who was close behind H\u00e4kkinen throughout lap one,<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\">{{cite web|title=Schu-master wins in Brazil|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3562|publisher=F1Racing.net|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318212739/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3562|archivedate=18 March 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> steered off the racing line to pass the latter for the lead heading into the Senna S chicane.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Barrichello [[Drafting (aerodynamics)|slipstreamed]] Coulthard on the start/finish straight and overtook him for third.<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> He then ran wide and Coulthard retook third. Barrichello retook the position by the end of lap two as Coulthard lost the use of the first three gears due to a gearbox fault and was slower in the slow-speed corners.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> At the front, Michael Schumacher extended his lead over H\u00e4kkinen to four seconds by lap four and to 15 seconds by lap 15 with a series of [[fastest lap]]s. In the meantime, Trulli passed Zonta for eighth, Button overtook Alesi for 13th and Heidfeld lost 16th to de la Rosa. Verstappen progressed from 11th to seventh by passing Villeneuve, Zonta, Frentzen and Fisichella as Alesi overtook Ralf Schumacher, Villeneuve, Zonta and Frentzen to advance to ninth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Three drivers retired from the race during this period: Wurz and Heidfeld had separate engine failures on lap seven and nine and Alesi stopped with an electrical failure at the Bico de Pato hairpin on lap 11.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\nAt the end of lap 14, Barrichello drew close to H\u00e4kkinen after the latter ran wide. He slipstreamed H\u00e4kkinen and turned left to pass him for second as he braked before the Senna S chicane to start the 15th lap.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> De la Rosa passed Herbert for 14th on that lap and Trulli overtook Irvine for fifth on lap 16.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> That lap, Villeneuve retired with a race-long gearbox problem. The Ferrari and McLaren teams employed different pit stop strategies \u2013 the Ferrari team planned for two stops whereas the McLaren squad scheduled one stop.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Michael Schumacher led by 17.6 seconds over the rest of the field when he commenced the first round of pit stops for fuel and tyres four laps later.<ref name=\"GF1Race\" /> He rejoined the track in third and Barrichello led the next two laps until his stop.<ref name=\"AutosportLapByLap\">{{cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8515|title=Brazilian Grand Prix: Lap by lap|date=26 March 2000|work=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103201/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8515|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref> On lap 21, Irvine lost control of the rear of his car entering the Bico de Pato hairpin and crashed against a tyre barrier. Six laps later, Barrichello entered the pit lane with a [[hydraulic motor]] problem that spread from the [[steering wheel]] to the throttle linkage.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=DF1RaceQuotes/> As Barrichello exited the car to retire a small fire was extinguished by his mechanics.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" />\n\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 01 (sk).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Michael Schumacher]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' took his second win of the season and 37th of his career.]]\n\nTrulli made the first of two stops from fourth at the end of the 28th lap and he emerged in seventh.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> At the front of the field, H\u00e4kkinen pulled away to lead Michael Schumacher by 12 seconds until he slowed with a loss of oil engine pressure on the 30th lap.<ref name=DF1RaceQuotes/><ref name=\"AutosportLapByLap\" /> He slowed and retired in his garage. Michael Schumacher retook the lead, with the yet-to-stop Coulthard second, Verstappen third and Fisichella fourth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Coulthard lapped to within a tenth of a second of Michael Schumacher as the latter slowed slightly due to an imbalance in all four of his tyres as Ralf Schumacher challenged Fisichella for fourth.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> On lap 32, Gen\u00e9 retired from eleventh with an engine failure.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Verstappen and his teammate de la Rosa made their first pit stops on laps 35 and 37. Four laps later, Frentzen was the first driver on a one-stop strategy to enter the pit lane.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Coulthard made his only stop on lap 43 and remained in second position. Michael Schumacher led by 48 seconds when he made his second pit stop on the 51st lap and retained the lead.<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> On the same lap, Fisichella made his only stop and kept third place.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\nOn lap 51, Herbert retired in the pit lane with a gearbox failure.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> De la Rosa lost concentration and went into a gravel trap four laps later. He rejoined without losing position.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> Button battled Verstappen and overtook him for seventh on the 56th lap as Trulli made a pit stop from fourth and rejoined the track in fifth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> From the 59th lap, Coulthard began to gain on Michael Schumacher, who slowed due to an [[oil pressure]] problem.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /><ref name=\"FIARace\" /> He could not draw close enough to pass, and Schumacher took his second victory of the season, his third in Brazil and the 37th of his career in a time of 1 hour, 31 minutes and 35.271 seconds at an average speed of {{Convert|200.404|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} over a distance of {{Convert|305.939|km|mi|abbr=on}} and 71 laps.<ref name=\"CF1Brazil2000\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/27/sports/plus-auto-racing-brazilian-grand-prix-schumacher-wins.html|title=Plus: Auto Racing \u2013 Brazilian Grand Prix; Schumacher Wins|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=12 May 2019|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512111105/https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/27/sports/plus-auto-racing-brazilian-grand-prix-schumacher-wins.html|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CollingsReport>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2186.htm|title=Timothy Collings' Brazilian GP Race Report|last=Collings|first=Timothy|date=26 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092838/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2186.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard followed 4.302 seconds later and Fisichella took third. Frentzen finished fourth, Trulli fifth and Ralf Schumacher sixth. Button, Verstappen, de la Rosa, Zonta and Mazzacane were the final finishers.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> The attrition rate was high; only 11 of the 20 starters finished the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60827984/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=9e4e0bb1|title=Triumphant Schumacher travels light; Motor Racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=40|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Post-race===\nThe top three drivers appeared on the podium to collect their trophies and spoke to the media in a later press conference.<ref name=\"regulations\" /> Michael Schumacher stated that pit stop strategy helped him to win the race: \"In the past, as you may remember, we could not overtake the McLaren entries, regardless of their strategy. Now we are looking a lot more competitive \u2013 which is where we wanted to be \u2013 and the season could hardly have started better than it has.\"<ref name=PressConf>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2191.htm|title=Post-Race Press Conference \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422093049/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2191.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard said his second-place finish provided him the start to his championship campaign after his gearbox problems: \"It must have been entertaining for those who had places to watch at the first corner. Given the circumstances, I am very happy with my six points.\"<ref name=PressConf/> Fisichella revealed that his car had understeer and oversteer for the first 15 laps until its grip and balance improved. Nonetheless, he said he was pleased to finish third, \"This is a great result and will help us to be even more competitive in the future. I am confident about the next race, when we will have some new aerodynamic parts.\"<ref name=PressConf/>\n\n[[File:David Coulthard 2007.jpg|thumb|upright|[[David Coulthard]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' was disqualified from second place due to an illegal front wing endplate on his car.]]\n\nAll of the top six finishers, except for Fisichella, were found to have excess wear on the wooden planks underneath their cars. The Ferrari, McLaren, Jordan and Williams teams filed a successful appeal against the regulation concerning illegal plank wear on the basis the bumpy racing surface caused it. All four teams were reinstated after a second inspection caused a {{frac|3|1|2}} hour delay.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8531|title=Schumacher cleared as race winner|date=27 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152054/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8531|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> During the inspection, the front wing endplates on Coulthard's car were found to be {{Convert|43|mm|cm|abbr=on}} above the ground and not {{Convert|50|mm|cm|abbr=on}} as stated in the regulations''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A75778273/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=6c8d1e8c|title=Motor Racing: McLaren 'were leant on': Team allege threats made to impound car if they did not toe line over disqualification|last=Henry|first=Alan|author-link=Alan Henry|date=28 March 2000|work=The Guardian|access-date=12 May 2019|page=9|via=General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2193.htm|title=Coulthard's car bumps him from 2nd spot|date=27 March 2000|work=Cape Argus|access-date=12 May 2019|agency=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230427/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2193.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Jo Bauer]], the FIA technical delegate, deemed this to have provided Coulthard with a competitive aerodynamic advantage and the stewards disqualified the driver six hours after the race. The technical director of McLaren [[Adrian Newey]] rejected an offer from the stewards to transport Coulthard's car to Paris for a fair hearing and agreed to a set of four measurements in S\u00e3o Paulo. McLaren then filed an appeal and stated the car's undertray and chassis was damaged and shifted by vibrations from the bumps on the racing surface.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60842541/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=08dcf78c|title=Coulthard left on wing and prayer; Motor racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=28 March 2000|work=The Times|access-date=12 May 2019|page=37|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 4 April, the appeal was heard by a five-man panel at a meeting of the FIA International Court of Appeal in Paris. They rejected McLaren's appeal during the 90-minute hearing and declared the result of the race final.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A103703782/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=4dd64b01|title=Coulthard loses appeal|last=Gowar|first=Rex|date=5 April 2000|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=066|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThis promoted every driver behind Coulthard one position; Button was reclassified sixth and became the [[List of Formula One driver records#Youngest drivers to score points|youngest driver to score a Formula One World Championship point]] at the age of 20 years, 2 months and 7 days old, breaking [[Ricardo Rodr\u00edguez (racing driver)|Ricardo Rodr\u00edguez]]'s record from the [[1962 Belgian Grand Prix]].{{#tag:ref|{{As of|2020}}, the record for the youngest driver to score a Formula One World Championship point is currently held by [[Max Verstappen]], who was 17 years and 166 days old when he finished seventh at the [[2015 Malaysian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Max Verstappen makes F1 history as youngest in points|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/motor/formula1/2015/03/29/max-verstappen-makes-f1-history-as-youngest-in-points/70625740/|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=Associated Press|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=\"n\"}}<ref>{{Cite journal|date=May 2000|title=Button Makes History|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/may-2000/5/button-makes-history|journal=[[Motor Sport (magazine)|Motor Sport]]|volume=LXXVI|pages=5|access-date=12 May 2019|number=5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152047/https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/may-2000/5/button-makes-history|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/22058/9429909/f1-records-dont-approve|title=F1 records showing their age|last=Esler|first=William|date=21 August 2014|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826050137/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/22058/9429909/f1-records-dont-approve|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> On 6 April, the organisers of the Brazilian Grand Prix were summoned to a meeting of the FIA General Assembly. They were fined $100,000 for the track's safety issues and for the three times qualifying was stopped due to falling advertising hoardings. The governing body ruled it as \"exceptional circumstances\" and allowed the track to remain as part of the series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/motorsport/2000/0407/148843-formula1/|title=Formula 1: FIA fine Brazilian GP organisers|date=7 April 2000|access-date=12 May 2019|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152051/https://www.rte.ie/sport/motorsport/2000/0407/148843-formula1/|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The president of the FIA [[Max Mosley]] said an increased fine or cancelling the race was not imposed because its organisers had submitted evidence to prevent either action from occurring, \"Bearing in mind that we allowed the Brazilian promoters to place the signs there \u2013 and they probably didn't know what potential there was for the failures which occurred \u2013 it seemed only fair to impose the comparatively modest penalty.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35623/1/interlagos-bumps-a-part-of-f1-says-max|title=Interlagos bumps a part of F1, says Max|date=9 April 2000|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152050/https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35623/1/interlagos-bumps-a-part-of-f1-says-max|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nH\u00e4kkinen spoke of his disappointment over retiring from the lead of the race, \"Nothing can describe how I feel, We have been quick all weekend, right the way through, so I am not happy to be leaving Brazil without any points. We have some work to do before the start of the European season.\"<ref name=CollingsReport/> Button was quoted in the press as stating his preference to score points on the track and not be awarded them in a court of appeal, \"I heard the news about David as I was making my way to the airport to fly back from Brazil \u2013 and I can't say it gave me any great feeling of joy. You want to earn any success through your driving skills, not someone else's misfortune.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9043|title=Button prefers to make point in races|date=29 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152050/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9043|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> [[Eddie Jordan]], the owner of the Jordan team, said that both his cars finishing the event demonstrated they could last a full race distance after retiring from the Australian Grand Prix with mechanical issues. Frentzen stated it was as if the team's season had commenced in Brazil and the team still required maintenance to improve their performance, \"But we are a very strong team with a good atmosphere, I get along well with Jarno and everything is fine so far.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2188.htm|title=Jordan Back in the Points in Brazil|last=Milliken|first=Mary|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422035436/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2188.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe gap in the Drivers' Championship after the race stood at 12 points in favour of Michael Schumacher with Fisichella moving from fifth to second as a result of his second-place finish. Barrichello dropped to third and Ralf Schumacher fell to fourth. Frentzen rounded out the top five.<ref name=\"points\" /> In the Constructors' Championship, Ferrari moved further ahead with 26 points and the Benetton team progressed from fourth to second. Jordan's first points of the season put them third while Williams and BAR were fourth and fifth with fifteen races left in the season.<ref name=\"points\" />\n\n===Race classification===\nDrivers who scored [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|championship points]] are denoted in '''bold'''.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|No.|Car num